# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ram-raiding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:ram-raiding/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] After Labour lost the 1990 election and its neoliberal faction lost influence, ACT was built mostly by Douglas' former party supporters as a new political party for 1996.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The introduction of proportional representation gave minor parties a greatly increased chance of getting into parliament.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Former Labour MP Richard Prebble won the safe Labour seat of Wellington Central and led ACT to win 6% of the vote in the first MMP election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] He continued as ACT party leader from after the election until 2004 when he was succeeded by Rodney Hide.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT was briefly led by former National Party leader Don Brash for the 2011 election, after which the party caucus was reduced to one seat.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] It continued as a single-MP party based out of the Epsom electorate until 2020.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT supported the Fifth National Government in confidence and supply from 2008 to 2017.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] It is currently one of the three parties in the National-led coalition government established in 2023.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The name comes from the initials of the Association of Consumers and Taxpayers, founded in 1993 by Sir Roger Douglas and Derek Quigley.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Douglas and Quigley intended the Association to serve as a pressure-group promoting Rogernomics—the name given to the radical free-market policies implemented by Douglas as Minister of Finance between 1984 and 1988.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The Association grew out of the 'Backbone club', a ginger group in the Labour Party that supported Douglas and his policies.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 1996, New Zealand switched to using the MMP electoral system.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The new electoral system gave smaller groups a much better chance of entering Parliament, and encouraged the Association to transform into a political party and contest elections.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The nascent party's manifesto was based upon a book written by Douglas entitled *Unfinished Business*.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Douglas served as ACT's first leader, but soon stood aside for Richard Prebble (his old ally from their days in the Labour Party).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Under Douglas, ACT had languished at 1% in opinion polls, but with Prebble's populist rhetoric the party increased in support.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the 1996 election, ACT fielded 56 list candidates.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Prebble won the Wellington Central electorate, and with 6.10% of the total party vote, ACT also sent seven list MPs to the 45th New Zealand Parliament.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the 1999 election, ACT obtained 7.04% of the party vote, making it eligible for nine list MPs.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the 2002 election, ACT obtained 7.14% of the party vote, making it eligible for nine list MPs.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 2 December 2004, both Douglas and Quigley announced that they would step down as patrons of ACT.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] They stated as the reason that they wished to have more freedom to disagree with the party publicly.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Prebble's sudden departure from the leadership of ACT in 2004 signalled a decline in the party's electoral fortunes.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Rodney Hide led ACT into the 2005 election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] It obtained 1.51% of the party vote, but due to Hide winning the seat of Epsom, it did not need to obtain the necessary 5% threshold of the party vote.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] This was only enough to allow one list MP Heather Roy, to join Hide in parliament.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the 2008 New Zealand general election, ACT fielded 61 list candidates, starting with Rodney Hide, Heather Roy, Sir Roger Douglas, John Boscawen, David Garrett and Hilary Calvert.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The election marked an improvement in ACT's fortunes.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Hide retained his Epsom seat and ACT's share of the party vote increased to 3.65% (up from the 1.5% gained in the 2005 election).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The combination allowed the party five MPs in total.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In addition, the National Party won the most seats overall, forming a minority government, the Fifth National Government of New Zealand, with the support of ACT as well as the Māori Party and United Future.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] John Key offered both Hide and Roy posts as Ministers outside Cabinet: Hide became Minister of Local Government, Minister for Regulatory Reform and Associate Minister of Commerce, while Roy became Minister of Consumer Affairs, Associate Minister of Defence and Associate Minister of Education.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Throughout 2009, there had been at least one reported ACT caucus coup attempt against Hide's leadership, believed to have been led by Deputy Leader Heather Roy and Roger Douglas.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] However, it faltered when Prime Minister Key supported Hide's retention and threatened a snap election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In addition, the party's polling of a lowly one to two percent in most opinion polls meant only Heather Roy might accompany Hide after any forthcoming general election, if Hide retained ACT's Epsom pivotal electorate seat.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 28 April 2011, Hide announced that he was resigning the ACT leadership in favour of former National Party leader and Reserve Bank Governor Don Brash who joined the party that morning.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Brash's leadership was unanimously approved by the party board and parliamentary caucus on 30 April.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Brash promised to focus the party on controlling government debt, equality between Māori and non-Māori, and rethinking the Emissions Trading Scheme, with a target of getting 15 percent of the party vote in the next election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In November 2011, a recording of a conversation held between John Key and the former National Party member and former Mayor of Auckland City John Banks, who had been selected as the new ACT candidate in Epsom, was leaked to *Herald on Sunday*.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] 3 News also obtained copies of the recording suggesting the two politicians were discussing issues related to ACT New Zealand's leadership.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the 2011 New Zealand general election, ACT fielded 55 list candidates, starting with new leader Don Brash, Catherine Isaac, Don Nicolson, John Banks, David Seymour and Chris Simmons.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The election was a disappointment for ACT, with the party's worst election result since it began in 1996.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] John Banks retained the Epsom seat for ACT, however the 34.2% majority held by Rodney Hide was severely cut back to 6.3% as large numbers of Labour and Green voters in Epsom tactically split their vote and gave their electorate vote to the National candidate Paul Goldsmith.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Nationwide, ACT received only 1.07% of the party vote, placing eighth out of 13 on party vote percentage.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] As a result, ACT were only entitled to one seat in the new Parliament, filled by John Banks.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Subsequently, Don Brash announced that he had stepped down as leader during his speech on election night.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Following the 2011 general election John Banks stated that he believed that the ACT brand "...just about had its use-by date..." and needed to be renamed and relaunched.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Their previous partners, the National Party, again won the most seats overall, and formed a minority government.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The Fifth National Government of New Zealand had ACT support as well as that of United Future and the Māori Party, providing the coalition with confidence and supply.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] At the ACT Board meeting of 2 February 2014, Jamie Whyte became the party's leader-elect, and David Seymour was made the ACT candidate for Epsom.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Kenneth Wang was appointed deputy leader on 15 April 2014.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the September 2014 general election, Seymour won his seat, and ACT moved from seventh to sixth place, despite a decline in their share of the popular vote.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Seymour took over as party leader on 3 October 2014.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Wang resigned as deputy leader on 9 July 2017, the same day ACT released its party list; Beth Houlbrooke was announced as his replacement.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party list had 39 candidates, none of whom were elected.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Party leader David Seymour was re-elected in the Epsom electorate, giving the party its only seat.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the run-up to the 2020 general election, ACT rose in opinion polls, from under 1% to close to 8%.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] This rise was attributed to Seymour's personal popularity.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Following the election, held on 17 October (postponed from September), ACT increased their share of the party vote to 7.6%, winning 10 seats including Seymour's Epsom seat and nine from the party list.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Some political analysts attributed ACT's strong result as partly benefiting from the collapse in support for the National Party and New Zealand First.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In late April 2021, the ACT party sponsored motion asking the New Zealand Parliament to debate and vote on the issue of human rights abuses against the Uyghur ethnic minority community in China's Xinjiang province.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In early May, the incumbent Labour Party revised the motion to raise concerns about human rights abuses in Xinjiang but omitting the term genocide, which was subsequently adopted by the New Zealand Parliament on 5 May.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In response, the Chinese Embassy claimed that the motion made "groundless accusations" of human rights abuses against China and constituted an interference in China's internal affairs.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 19 May 2021, the ACT Party opposed Green Party MP Golriz Ghahraman's motion calling for members of parliament to recognise the rights of Palestinians to self-determination and statehood while reaffirming its support for a two-state solution to the Israel-Palestine conflict.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Final results of the 2023 general election indicated that ACT won 8.64% of the party vote, resulting in 11 seats.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Seymour retained his Epsom seat and Deputy Leader Brooke van Velden won the Tāmaki electorate.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In November 2023, ACT entered into a coalition deal with the National party to form part of the Sixth National Government of New Zealand.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] As part of National's coalition agreement with ACT, the Government would adopt ACT's policies of restoring interest deductibility for rental properties and pet bonds.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In addition to adopting National's youth crime and gang policies, the new Government would adopt ACT's policies of rewriting firearms legislation.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The new Government would also scrap the previous Labour Government's fair pay agreements, proposed hate speech legislation, co-governance policies, Auckland light rail, Three Waters reform programme, and Māori Health Authority.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The Government would also establish a new Ministry for Regulation headed by Seymour that would review the quality of new and existing legislation.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Within the National-led coalition government, Seymour became the first Minister for Regulation and was designated as Deputy Prime Minister from 31 May 2025.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Van Velden became Minister of Internal Affairs and Minister for Workplace Relations and Safety.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Nicole McKee became Minister for Courts and Associate Minister of Justice (firearms).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Andrew Hoggard was appointed as Minister for Biosecurity and Food Safety while Karen Chhour was appointed as Minister for Children and Minister for the Prevention of Family and Sexual Violence.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Simon Court was appointed as Parliamentary Under-Secretary for the Minister for Infrastructure and RMA Reform.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Opposition to the bill included criticism from Te Pāti Māori co-leader Debbie Ngarewa-Packer, who accused Seymour of deliberately trying to divide New Zealand, and outgoing Labour MP Kelvin Davis, who stated that his party will continue to oppose the "Pākehā Government spiders".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 7 June 2024, Stuff journalist Tova O'Brien reported that allegations of intimidation, unfair treatment of women and a "trainwreck campaign" within the ACT party had led six staff members and volunteers to resign following the 2023 general election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In addition, the party's board was facing a vote of no confidence.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Complainants likened elements of the 2023 election campaign to the *Hunger Games* and alleged that candidates and volunteers were bullied.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In response to the allegations, the ACT party confirmed that it had conducted an independent review into its campaign.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party's president Catherine Isaac stated that the party had accepted the review's recommendations and acknowledged that political campaigns could be stressful on people, who also had to balance their lives and careers.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] During ACT's annual rally on 9 June, Seymour downplayed allegations of a "culture of fear" within the ACT party and reiterated the party's support for the review's recommendations.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In his speech, Seymour said that the party's support had grown by 1,000 percent in the past five years and set out a 15% voter target for the 2026 general election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In early July 2024, ACT invoked the "agree to disagree" provision of its coalition agreement after the National-led government decided to progress the Fair Digital News Bargaining Bill, which had been introduced by the previous Labour Government.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In late February 2025, the Government agreed to support the ACT party's proposed legislation to extend the parliamentary term from three to four years.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In mid March 2025, Seymour confirmed that ACT would be fielding candidates during the 2025 New Zealand local elections, marking the first time the party would contest local body elections.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 6 May 2025 ACT declined to support the National Party's proposed legislation forcing social media platforms to restrict access to users under the age of 16 years.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Consequently, National was unable to introduce the legislation as a government bill and had to introduce it as a member's bill.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 11 May, ACT invoked the "agree to disagree" clause of its coalition agreement after the National Party declined to support McKee's call for a review of the New Zealand government's firearms registry, and that a more "thorough and independent" review be conducted for the 2025-2026 financial year.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On 31 May 2025, David Seymour succeeded Winston Peters as deputy prime minister, under the terms of the coalition agreement in 2023.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] He became the first ACT deputy prime minister.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In June 2025, the party announced their first candidates for the 2025 local elections, who campaigned under the ACT Local banner.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Logistics manager James Ebbett would run for the Central Hawke's Bay District Council, retired pharmacist David Ross for the Tasman District Council, and local businessman Nathan Atkins for the Waimakariri District Council.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In late January 2026, ACT opposed the introduction of new legislation targeting modern slavery.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] National and Labour subsequently announced they would co-sponsor a new bill targeting modern slavery.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In late June 2026, the associate justice minister Nicole McKee was appointed as ACT's deputy leader during the party's annual general meeting in Auckland.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] According to former party leader Rodney Hide, ACT's values are "individual freedom, personal responsibility, doing the best for our natural environment and for smaller, smarter government in its goals of a prosperous economy, a strong society, and a quality of life that is the envy of the world".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT states that it adheres to classical-liberal and small (or limited) government principles coupled with what the party considers as a high regard for individual freedom and personal responsibility.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT has been characterised as a conservative, classical liberal and libertarian party, although its stances have changed under successive leadership and the party's support base has drawn a "big tent" and a "broad church" of voters.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT's platform featured conservative populist policies under former leaders Richard Prebble (in office: 1996–2004) and Rodney Hide (2004–2011).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Under the leadership of David Seymour (in office from 2014 onwards), commentators have identified a shift in policy to a more libertarian outlook.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Seymour has stated that he does not view populism as the way to govern a country or to stimulate growth, and has accused the centre-left New Zealand Labour Party of engaging in populism in its policies on business, spending and tax.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The ACT Party emphasises the importance of property rights.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT wants to reduce or remove some government programmes which it sees as unnecessary and wasteful, and to increase self-reliance by encouraging individuals to take responsibility to pay for services traditionally paid for by governments.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Under leader Rodney Hide, ACT New Zealand had primarily focused on two main policy areas: taxation and crime (law-and-order issues).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] At the 2011 general election, ACT advocated lowering tax rates and also supported something approaching a flat tax, in which tax rates would not be graduated based on wealth or income, so that every taxpayer would pay the same proportion of their income in tax.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The flat tax-rate that ACT proposed was approximately 15%, with no tax on the first $25,000 for those who opt out of state-provided accident, sickness and healthcare cover.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] As at 2021, the party proposed reducing GST and decreasing the marginal tax rate paid by those on the median wage, but did not advocate a flat tax rate.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] During the 2020 general election, the ACT party campaigned on a broad policy platform.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] It prioritised economic recovery (*see: COVID-19 pandemic in New Zealand § Long-term effects*), keeping national debt low, and signing up to a CANZUK agreement which would enable free movement of people and goods between the United Kingdom, New Zealand, Canada and Australia.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party wants to protect freedom of expression and to limit funding for universities that do not uphold freedom of speech on campus.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] It supports immigration while it calls for compulsory measures for immigrants to assimilate and for limiting citizenship or permanent-residency status to those who pledge to uphold the values of New Zealand.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] On its website, ACT states "that all New Zealanders should have the same fundamental rights, regardless of race, religion, sexuality or gender".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party says "the rights of victims should trump the rights of criminals" and has a number of tough-on-crime policies focused primarily on trying to control gangs.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Party leader, David Seymour, wants to reintroduce the "three strikes law" (repealed in 2022 by the Labour Government) and to impose three-year prison sentences—without parole—on anyone who commits three burglaries.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT advocates repealing New Zealand's 2019 firearms legislation, and taking a "tougher" stance on criminals who repeatedly offend and on those found guilty of violent crimes, while also supporting rehabilitation programs.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In September 2022, the ACT Party proposed fitting ankle bracelets on young offenders aged between 11 and 14 to combat juvenile crime, particularly ram-raiding.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Party leader Seymour argued that ankle bracelets were non-intrusive and would allow police to monitor young offenders.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In response, Police Minister Chris Hipkins stated that the Labour Government was not considering the use of ankle bracelets for young offenders but would keep "all options on the table".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] National Party leader Christopher Luxon and education spokesperson Erica Stanford initially indicated that they would not support ACT's ankle-bracelet policy, with Stanford describing it as "heartbreaking".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] New Zealand rugby-league player Sir Graham Lowe criticised the ankle-bracelet policy, while Waikato retailer Ash Parmer supported it.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In November 2022, National reversed its initial opposition to fitting young offenders with ankle bracelets; with justice spokesperson Paul Goldsmith stating that a law change was necessary to impose electronic monitoring or intensive supervision on child offenders aged under 12 years.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In May 2023, Seymour announced that ACT, if elected into government, would build youth-detention centres run by the Department of Corrections.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Members of ACT's caucus in parliament voted five to four in favour of the Civil Union Act 2004 which gave the option of legal recognition to (among others) same-sex couples.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] A majority within the caucus also supported the legalisation of brothels by the Prostitution Reform Act 2003.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2005, both of ACT's MPs, Rodney Hide and Heather Roy, voted for the Marriage (Gender Clarification) Amendment Bill 2005, which would have banned the possibility of introducing same-sex marriage in New Zealand in the future perspective.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2013, leader John Banks (the party's sole MP from 2011 to 2014) voted in favour of the Marriage (Definition of Marriage) Amendment Bill at its third reading, a law which legalised same-sex marriage in New Zealand.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT leader David Seymour supported the legalisation of assisted dying.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2018, he introduced a member's bill, the End of Life Choice Bill, which aimed to legalise euthanasia in New Zealand.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The law passed in 2019, was approved by the public in a 2020 referendum, and took full effect in 2021.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Grant Duncan cited the euthanasia law as an example of ACT neoliberalism.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2020, Seymour voted for the Abortion Legislation Act which introduced abortion on request.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] However, he criticised a particular aspect of this law which created "free protest zones" which would ban protests near abortion clinics, saying this limits freedom of expression.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2021, ACT expressed support for liberalisation of surrogacy law so as to facilitate availability of surrogate services to heterosexual and same-sex couples as well.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT proposes abolition of the Māori electorate seats in the New Zealand Parliament, arguing the seats are "an anachronism and offensive to the principle of equal citizenship" and that Māori MPs have been elected in general elections on other lists without special assistance.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party also wants to reduce the number of MPs in parliament from 120 to 100.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In March 2022, ACT campaigned on holding a referendum on Māori co-governance arrangements as a condition for entering into coalition with the National Party.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Seymour has argued that the 1840 Treaty of Waitangi was not a partnership between the New Zealand Crown and Māori, and that co-governance arrangements created resentment and division.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In addition, ACT announced that it would introduce a new law defining the principles of the Treaty of Waitangi if elected into government following the 2023 election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] This law would only come into effect following a referendum held at the 2026 general election.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT's proposed referendum and law would affect co-governance arrangements at several Crown Research Institutes, state-owned enterprises and healthcare providers such as Te Aka Whai Ora (the Māori Health Authority).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] However, Seymour indicated that the new law would preserve existing co-governance arrangements with the Waikato, Ngāi Tahu, Tūhoe and Whanganui iwi (tribes).
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Māori Party co-leader Debbie Ngarewa-Packer and Professor Linda Tuhiwai Smith described ACT's proposed co-governance referendum and policies as being motivated by racism and reflecting a Pākehā unwillingness to share power.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Similarly, Waikato leader Rahui Papa claimed that ACT's co-governance policies clashed with the second and third articles of the treaty which (he argued) guaranteed Māori participation in the social sector.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In response, Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern reiterated her government's commitment to co-governance arrangements.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Meanwhile, National Party leader Christopher Luxon refused to commit to a referendum on co-governance, but acknowledged that further clarity on co-governance was needed.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In October 2022, ACT released a discussion document entitled "Democracy or co-government?" which proposed a new Treaty Principles Act that would end the focus on partnership between Māori and the Crown and interpret "tino rangatiratanga" solely as property rights.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] By contrast, most scholars of the Māori language define "tino rangatiratanga" as the equivalent of "self-determination" in the English language.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The proposed Treaty Principles Act does not mention Māori, the Crown, iwi (tribes), and hapū (subgroups) but refers only to "New Zealanders".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT Party leader Seymour refused to identify whom his party had consulted when developing its co-governance and Treaty of Waitangi policies, particularly its redefinition of "tino rangatiratanga" as property rights.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] As part of ACT's non-racial (colour-blind) policies, its social-development spokesperson Karen Chhour advocated the abolition of Te Aka Whai Ora.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Following the 2023 election and the formation of a National-led coalition government, ACT embarked on a public information campaign in early February 2024 to promote its Treaty Principles Bill.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] This campaign includes the creation of a new website called "treaty.nz," which has a Questions and Answers section outlining the party's approach to the principles of the Treaty of Waitangi and a video featuring Seymour.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] Seymour also contested claims that the opposition was trying to rewrite or abolish the Treaty of Waitangi.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The public information campaign also came after a leaked Justice Ministry memo claimed that the proposed bill clashed with the text of the Treaty.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In February 2016, ACT deleted this climate-change policy from their website, and party leader David Seymour criticised the Green Party for doing "bugger all for the environment".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT placed Chris Baillie fourth on its party list of candidates in the 2020 election; he has received criticism over his views on climate change, and been labelled a climate-change sceptic.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In the runup to the 2020 election, Environmental Defence Society chief executive Gary Taylor said that even ACT had moved its position from where it had been.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In early December 2020, the New Zealand Parliament officially declared a climate emergency, of which ACT was critical, stating, "Today's climate emergency was a triumph for post-rational politics with feelings rather than facts driving the Government's response to climate change".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party supports repealing the 2019 "Zero Carbon Act".
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In 2019, ACT expressed sympathy with the Hong Kong pro-democracy protestors during the 2019–20 Hong Kong protests with party leader David Seymour speaking at a Hong Kong pro-democracy rally at the University of Auckland.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The party argued that the New Zealand government should condemn efforts by the Chinese government to restrict freedom of speech in Hong Kong and criticised the Chinese Consulate-General for praising a Chinese student who had assaulted a pro-democracy activist in Auckland.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] In response to the Gaza war, Seymour as ACT leader issued a statement in support of Israel and condemned Hamas terrorism.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] ACT also accused Labour Foreign Minister Nanaia Mahuta of not explicitly opposing Hamas' actions.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The ACT party board appoints a leader and deputy leader recommended by the party caucus; when the party leader is not a member of parliament, a separate parliamentary leader is chosen by the caucus.
[src:ram-raiding/act-new-zealand] The organisation outside parliament is led by a party president and party vice-president.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster was born in 1975 or 1976 in Dunedin, and grew up in Auckland, attending King's College.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] His father is Professor Gregor Coster, the former Dean of the Wellington Faculty of Health.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster holds a Bachelor of Laws (Honours) from the University of Auckland and a Master of Public Management from Victoria University of Wellington.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster joined the New Zealand Police in 1997.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] While serving, Coster studied law at the University of Auckland, and briefly left the Police to work for Meredith Connell as a Crown prosecutor.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] He returned to the Police in 2005 in a supervisory position and went on to serve as Auckland City Area Commander, from 2009 to 2013, and Southern District Commander, from 2013 to 2015.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] At the time, he was the youngest district commander ever appointed.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] After attaining the Wellington-based position of assistant commissioner for strategy and transformation in 2015, Coster was seconded to the Ministry of Justice in 2016 where he was a deputy chief executive leading a court reform project.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Returning to the Police in 2018, Coster was an acting deputy commissioner, during which time he was involved with weapons reforms following the March 2019 Christchurch mosque shootings.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster was appointed as the Commissioner of the New Zealand Police on 9 March 2020.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Another candidate as Commissioner was Mike Clement, the then-Deputy Commissioner.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] He started his term on 3 April 2020 at age 44, becoming the youngest person to assume the role.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In mid-February 2021, Coster's efforts to combat gang and gun violence was criticised by the National Party's Justice spokesperson Simon Bridges, who described Coster as a "wokester commissioner" in a Twitter post.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] On 25 February, Coster defended the Police's "policing by consent" policies in response to criticism by Bridges during a Justice select committee hearing at the New Zealand Parliament.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] During the 2022 Wellington protest, Coster unsuccessfully attempted to convince anti-vaccine mandate protesters to voluntarily remove their illegally parked vehicles from the area around the New Zealand Parliament in mid February 2022.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] After protesters refused to vacate the Parliament grounds, he ruled out pursuing enforcement action against protesters due to concerns about violence.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster instead announced that Police would pursue a policy of "negotiation and de-escalation." Coster's decision to rule out "enforcement action" was criticised by the National Party's police spokesman Mark Mitchell, who claimed that Coster had lost credibility as Police Commissioner.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] On 2 March, Police evicted the remaining anti-mandate protesters following a violent riot.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In its review of the policing of the protest, the Independent Police Conduct Authority found that, despite a range of recommendations for change, Police did a good job and served the public of New Zealand well in dealing with a difficult and complex set of events.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Following the formation of a National-led coalition government after the 2023 New Zealand general election, Police Minister Mitchell met with Coster in early December 2023 to set out expectations on police and combating gangs.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster agreed to the Minister's expectations.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In July 2024, Coster announced he would step down as commissioner at the end of his term, which was scheduled for April 2025.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] That September, it was announced Coster would leave the role sooner to start his next position as chief executive of the government's new Social Investment Agency in November 2024.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Acting Public Service Commissioner Heather Baggot stated she was "very pleased" to appoint Coster to his new role, and that "[Coster] is a highly respected and impressive public service leader who has considerable experience delivering initiatives to address complex social issues".
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In contrast, President of the Police Association of New Zealand, Chris Cahill, took a different view commenting that Coster's resignation was "probably a good call" and that he "hasn't been everyones favourite commissioner".
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster completed his term as commissioner on 10 November, and was succeeded in the role in an interim capacity by the deputy commissioner Tania Kura the following day.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] On 11 November 2024, Coster began his new role as Secretary for Social Investment and Chief Executive of the Social Investment Agency.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] The agency was established to lead the government's social investment strategy, which aims to improve outcomes for vulnerable New Zealanders through evidence-based policy and targeted funding.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster oversees the implementation of a $190 million Social Investment Fund, designed to support at least 20 initiatives over four years, with a focus on early intervention and long-term impact.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] His appointment was welcomed by the Public Service Commission, which cited his track record in addressing complex social issues and his pragmatic leadership style.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] On 3 December 2025, Coster resigned from his position at the Social Investment Agency, effective immediately, after being placed on leave following the release of an Independent Police Conduct Authority report into police handling of allegations against former Deputy Commissioner Jevon McSkimming.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In confirming his departure, Public Service Commissioner Sir Brian Roche said the IPCA had found serious leadership failures but no evidence of corruption or a deliberate cover-up, and Coster stated that he accepted responsibility for his decisions and apologised to the complainant.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] The report centred on how police leadership, including Coster, handled allegations of sexual offending made by a former police employee against then–Deputy Commissioner Jevon McSkimming.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] The IPCA found that Coster and other senior executives delayed referring the woman’s complaints to the authority and attempted to influence the course of the investigation once it began.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] According to the report, Coster expressed concern that the IPCA’s inquiry could “increase Jevon’s victimisation” and adversely affect McSkimming’s prospects of becoming Police Commissioner.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] It also found that senior leaders appeared “unduly preoccupied” with protecting McSkimming’s career and viewed him as a victim rather than an alleged offender.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] During an exclusive interview with TVNZ journalist Jack Tame on 7 December 2025, Coster said that he had briefed both former Police Minister Chris Hipkins and Mark Mitchell on two separate occasions in 2022 and 2024 about McSkimming's extramarital affair before the case became public in 2025.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] He said he was unable to provide proof that those conversations with these ministers had occurred.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] Coster also disputed remarks by Public Service Minister Judith Collins suggesting that the police executive leadership had a problem with corruption.
[src:ram-raiding/andrew-coster] In response, both Hipkins and Mitchell issued statements disputing Coster's recollections of those events and defended the IPCA's inquiry's findings into Coster's shortcomings.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs are known by a variety of other names, including automatic teller machines (ATMs) in the United States (sometimes redundantly as "ATM machine").
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In Canada, the term **automated banking machine** (**ABM**) is also used, although ATM is also very commonly used in Canada, with many Canadian organizations using ATM rather than ABM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In British English, the terms **cashpoint**, **cash machine** and **hole in the wall** are also used.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs that are not operated by a financial institution are known as "white-label" ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Using an ATM, customers can access their bank deposit or credit accounts in order to make a variety of financial transactions, most notably cash withdrawals and balance checking, as well as transferring credit to and from mobile phones.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs can also be used to withdraw cash in a foreign country.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] If the currency being withdrawn from the ATM is different from that in which the bank account is denominated, the money will be converted at the financial institution's exchange rate.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] According to the ATM Industry Association (ATMIA), as of 2015, there were close to 3.5 million ATMs installed worldwide.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] However, the use of ATMs is gradually declining with the increase in cashless payment systems.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The idea of out-of-hours cash distribution was first put into practice in Japan, the United Kingdom, and Sweden.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 1960, Armenian-American inventor Luther Simjian invented an automated deposit machine (accepting coins, cash and cheques) although it did not have cash dispensing features.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] His US patent was first filed on 30 June 1960 and granted on 26 February 1963.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The roll-out of this machine, called Bankograph, was delayed by a couple of years, due in part to Simjian's Reflectone Electronics Inc. being acquired by Universal Match Corporation.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] An experimental Bankograph was installed in New York City in 1961 by the City Bank of New York, but removed after six months due to the lack of customer acceptance.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 1962, Adrian Ashfield invented the idea of a card system to securely identify a user and control and monitor the dispensing of goods or services.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This was granted UK Patent 959,713 in June 1964 and assigned to Kins Developments Limited.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 1966, a Japanese device called the "Computer Loan Machine" dispensed cash as a three-month loan at an annual interest rate of 5% upon inserting a credit card.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] However, little is known about the device.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A cash machine was installed at Barclays Bank, Enfield, North London in the United Kingdom, on 27 June 1967.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This is generally considered the world's first ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This machine was inaugurated by English actor Reg Varney as part of the launch publicity.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This invention is credited to the engineering team led by John Shepherd-Barron of printing firm De La Rue, who was awarded an OBE in the 2005 New Year Honours.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Transactions were initiated by inserting paper cheques issued by a teller or cashier, marked with carbon-14 for machine readability and security, which in a later model were matched with a four-digit personal identification number (PIN).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The Barclays–De La Rue machine (called De La Rue Automatic Cash System or DACS) beat the Swedish saving banks' and a company called Metior's machine (a device called Bankomat) by a mere nine days and British Westminster Bank's Smith Industries Chubb system (called Chubb MD2) by a month.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The online version of the Swedish machine is listed to have been operational on 6 May 1968, while claiming to be the first online ATM in the world, ahead of similar claims by IBM and Lloyds Bank in 1971, and Oki in 1970.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The collaboration of a small start-up called Speytec and Midland Bank developed a fourth machine which was marketed after 1969 in Europe and the US by the Burroughs Corporation.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The patent for this device (GB1329964) was filed in September 1969 (and granted in 1973) by John David Edwards, Leonard Perkins, John Henry Donald, Peter Lee Chappell, Sean Benjamin Newcombe, and Malcom David Roe.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Both the DACS and MD2 accepted only a single-use token or voucher which was retained by the machine, while the Speytec worked with a card with a magnetic stripe at the back.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] They used principles including Carbon-14 and low-coercivity magnetism in order to make fraud more difficult.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The idea of a PIN stored on the card was developed by a group of engineers working at Smiths Group on the Chubb MD2 in 1965 and which has been credited to James Goodfellow (patent GB1197183 filed on 2 May 1966 with Anthony Davies).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The essence of this system was that it enabled the verification of the customer with the debited account without human intervention.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This patent is also the earliest instance of a complete "currency dispenser system" in the patent record.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This patent was filed on 5 March 1968 in the US (US 3543904) and granted on 1 December 1970.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It had a profound influence on the industry as a whole.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Not only did future entrants into the cash dispenser market such as NCR Corporation and IBM license Goodfellow's PIN system, but a number of later patents reference this patent as "Prior Art Device".
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Asea Meteor) manufacturers quickly spread out.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] For example, given its link with Barclays, Bank of Scotland deployed a DACS in 1968 under the 'Scotcash' brand.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Customers were given personal code numbers to activate the machines, similar to the modern PIN.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] They were also supplied with £10 vouchers.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] These were fed into the machine, and the corresponding amount was debited from the customer's account.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A Chubb-made ATM appeared in Sydney in 1969.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This was the first ATM installed in Australia.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The machine only dispensed $25 at a time and the bank card itself would be mailed to the user after the bank had processed the withdrawal.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Asea Metior's Bancomat was the first ATM installed in Spain on 9 January 1969, in central Madrid by Banesto.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This device dispensed 1,000 peseta bills (1 to 5 max).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Each user had to introduce a security personal key using a combination of the ten numeric buttons.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In March of the same year an ad with the instructions to use the Bancomat was published in the same newspaper.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In West Germany, the first ATM was installed in the 50,000-people university city of Tübingen on 27 May 1968, by Kreissparkasse Tübingen.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It was built by Aalen-based safe builder Ostertag AG in cooperation with AEG-Telefunken.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Each of the 1,000 selected users were given a double-bit key to open the safe with "Geldausgabe" written on it, a plastic identification card, and ten punched cards.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] One punch card functioned as a withdrawal slip for a 100 DM bill, the maximum limit for daily use was 400 DM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] After looking firsthand at the experiences in Europe, in 1968 the ATM, was pioneered in the US by Donald Wetzel, who was a department head at a company called Docutel.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Docutel was a subsidiary of Recognition Equipment Inc of Dallas, Texas, which was producing optical scanning equipment and had instructed Docutel to explore automated baggage handling and automated gasoline pumps.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] On 2 September 1969, Chemical Bank installed a prototype ATM in the US at its branch in Rockville Centre, New York.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The first ATMs were designed to dispense a fixed amount of cash when a user inserted a specially coded card.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A Chemical Bank advertisement boasted "On Sept.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] 2 our bank will open at 9:00 and never close again." Chemical's ATM, initially known as a Docuteller was designed by Donald Wetzel and his company Docutel.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Chemical executives were initially hesitant about the electronic banking transition given the high cost of the early machines.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Additionally, executives were concerned that customers would resist having machines handling their money.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 1995, the Smithsonian National Museum of American History recognized Docutel and Wetzel as the inventors of the networked ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] To show confidence in Docutel, Chemical installed the first four production machines in a marketing test that proved they worked reliably, customers would use them and even pay a fee for usage.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Based on this, banks around the country began to experiment with ATM installations.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] By 1974, Docutel had acquired 70 percent of the US market; but as a result of the early 1970s worldwide recession and its reliance on a single product line, Docutel lost its independence and was forced to merge with the US subsidiary of Olivetti.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Patent # 3,761,682 Archived 5 September 2017 at the Wayback Machine; the application had been filed in October 1971.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] However, the US patent record cites at least three previous applications from Docutel, all relevant to the development of the ATM and where Wetzel does not figure, namely US Patent # 3,662,343 Archived 5 September 2017 at the Wayback Machine, U.S.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Patent # 3651976 Archived 5 September 2017 at the Wayback Machine and U.S.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Patent # 3,68,569 Archived 5 September 2017 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] These patents are all credited to Kenneth S.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Goldstein, MR Karecki, TR Barnes, GR Chastian and John D.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In April 1971, Busicom began to manufacture ATMs based on the first commercial microprocessor, the Intel 4004.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Busicom manufactured these microprocessor-based automated teller machines for several buyers, with NCR Corporation as the main customer.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Mohamed Atalla invented the first hardware security module (HSM), dubbed the "Atalla Box", a security system which encrypted PIN and ATM messages, and protected offline devices with an un-guessable PIN-generating key.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] He founded Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla) in 1972, and commercially launched the "Atalla Box" in 1973.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The product was released as the Identikey.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It was a card reader and customer identification system, providing a terminal with plastic card and PIN capabilities.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The Identikey system consisted of a card reader console, two customer PIN pads, an intelligent controller and a built-in electronic interface package.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The device consisted of two keypads, one for the customer and one for the teller.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It allowed the customer to type in a secret code, which is transformed by the device, using a microprocessor, into another code for the teller.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] During a transaction, the customer's account number was read by the card reader.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This process replaced manual entry and avoided possible keystroke errors.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It allowed users to replace traditional customer verification methods such as signature verification and test questions with a secure PIN system.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The success of the "Atalla Box" led to the wide adoption of hardware security modules in ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Its PIN verification process was similar to the later IBM 3624.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Atalla's HSM products protect 250 million card transactions every day as of 2013, and secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The IBM 2984 was a modern ATM and came into use at Lloyds Bank, High Street, Brentwood, Essex, United Kingdom in December 1972.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The IBM 2984 was designed at the request of Lloyds Bank.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The 2984 Cash Issuing Terminal was a true ATM, similar in function to today's machines and named Cashpoint by Lloyds Bank.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Cashpoint is still a registered trademark of Lloyds Bank plc in the UK but is often used as a generic trademark to refer to ATMs of all UK banks.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] All were online and issued a variable amount which was immediately deducted from the account.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A small number of 2984s were supplied to a US bank.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A couple of well-known historical models of ATMs include the Atalla Box, IBM 3614, IBM 3624 and 473x series, Diebold 10xx and TABS 9000 series, NCR 1780 and earlier NCR 770 series.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The first switching system to enable shared automated teller machines between banks went into production operation on 3 February 1979, in Denver, Colorado, in an effort by Colorado National Bank of Denver and Kranzley and Company of Cherry Hill, New Jersey.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 2012, a new ATM at Royal Bank of Scotland allowed customers to withdraw cash up to £130 without a card by inputting a six-digit code requested through their smartphones.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs can be placed at any location but are most often placed near or inside banks, shopping centers, airports, railway stations, metro stations, grocery stores, gas stations, restaurants, and other locations.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs are also found on cruise ships and on some US Navy ships, where sailors can draw out their pay.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] On-premises ATMs are typically more advanced, multi-function machines that complement a bank branch's capabilities, and are thus more expensive.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Off-premises machines are deployed by financial institutions where there is a simple need for cash, so they are generally cheaper single-function devices.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Independent ATM deployers unaffiliated with banks install and maintain white-label ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In the US, Canada and some Gulf countries, banks may have drive-thru lanes providing access to ATMs using an automobile.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In recent times, countries like India and some countries in Africa are installing solar-powered ATMs in rural areas.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The world's highest ATM is located at the Khunjerab Pass in Pakistan.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Installed at an elevation of 4,693 metres (15,397 ft) by the National Bank of Pakistan, it is designed to work in temperatures as low as -40-degree Celsius.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Most ATMs are connected to interbank networks, enabling people to withdraw and deposit money from machines not belonging to the bank where they have their accounts or in the countries where their accounts are held (enabling cash withdrawals in local currency).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Some examples of interbank networks include NYCE, PULSE, PLUS, Cirrus, AFFN, Interac, Interswitch, STAR, LINK, MegaLink, and BancNet.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs rely on the authorization of a financial transaction by the card issuer or other authorizing institution on a communications network.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This is often performed through an ISO 8583 messaging system.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In some cases, these fees are charged solely to users who are not customers of the bank that operates the ATM; in other cases, they apply to all users.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In addition to methods employed for transaction security and secrecy, all communications traffic between the ATM and the Transaction Processor may also be encrypted using methods such as SSL.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] There are no hard international or government-compiled numbers totaling the complete number of ATMs in use worldwide.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Estimates as of 2015 developed by ATMIA placed the number of ATMs in use at 3 million units, or approximately 1 ATM per 3,000 people in the world.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] To simplify the analysis of ATM usage around the world, financial institutions generally divide the world into seven regions, based on the penetration rates, usage statistics, and features deployed.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Four regions (USA, Canada, Europe, and Japan) have high numbers of ATMs per million people.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Despite the large number of ATMs, there is additional demand for machines in the Asia/Pacific area as well as in Latin America.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Macau may have the highest density of ATMs at 254 ATMs per 100,000 adults.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] With the uptake of cashless payment solutions in the late 2010s, ATM numbers and usage started to decline.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This happened first in developed countries at a time when ATM numbers were still increasing in Asia and Africa.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] As of 2021, there had been a global decline in the number of ATMs in use, with the average dropping to 39 per 100,000 adults from a peak of 41 per 100,000 adults in 2020.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Business owners often lease ATMs from service providers.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] However, based on the economies of scale, the price of equipment has dropped to the point where many business owners are simply paying for ATMs using a credit card.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] New ADA voice and text-to-speech guidelines imposed in 2010, but required by March 2012 have forced many ATM owners to either upgrade non-compliant machines or dispose them if they are not upgradable, and purchase new compliant equipment.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This has created an avenue for hackers and thieves to obtain ATM hardware at junkyards from improperly disposed decommissioned machines.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The vault of an ATM is within the footprint of the device itself and is where items of value are kept.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Scrip cash dispensers, which print a receipt or scrip instead of cash, do not incorporate a vault.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATM vaults are supplied by manufacturers in several grades.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Factors influencing vault grade selection include cost, weight, regulatory requirements, ATM type, operator risk avoidance practices and internal volume requirements.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Industry standard vault configurations include Underwriters Laboratories UL-291 "Business Hours" and Level 1 Safes, RAL TL-30 derivatives, and CEN EN 1143-1 - CEN III and CEN IV.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATM manufacturers recommend that a vault be attached to the floor to prevent theft, though there is a record of a theft conducted by tunneling into an ATM floor.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] With the migration to commodity Personal Computer hardware, standard commercial "off-the-shelf" operating systems and programming environments can be used inside of ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Typical platforms previously used in ATM development include RMX or OS/2.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Today, the vast majority of ATMs worldwide use Microsoft Windows.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In early 2014, 95% of ATMs were running Windows XP.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A small number of deployments may still be running older versions of the Windows OS, such as Windows NT, Windows CE, or Windows 2000, even though Microsoft only supports Windows 10 and Windows 11.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] There is a computer industry security view that general public desktop operating systems have greater risks as operating systems for cash dispensing machines than other types of operating systems like (secure) real-time operating systems (RTOS).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] RISKS Digest has many articles about ATM operating system vulnerabilities.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Linux is also finding some reception in the ATM marketplace.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] An example of this is Banrisul, the largest bank in the south of Brazil, which has replaced the MS-DOS operating system in its ATMs with Linux.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Banco do Brasil is also migrating ATMs to Linux.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Indian-based Vortex Engineering is manufacturing ATMs that operate only with Linux.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] NCR's AANDC v3.x.y, where x.y are subversions).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Most major ATM manufacturers provide software packages that implement these protocols.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Newer protocols such as IFX have yet to find wide acceptance by transaction processors.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] With the move to a more standardized software base, financial institutions have been increasingly interested in the ability to pick and choose the application programs that drive their equipment.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] WOSA/XFS, now known as CEN XFS (or simply XFS), provides a common API for accessing and manipulating the various devices of an ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] J/XFS is a Java implementation of the CEN XFS API.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] While the perceived benefit of XFS is similar to Java's "write once, run anywhere" mantra, often different ATM hardware vendors have different interpretations of the XFS standard.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The result of these differences in interpretation means that ATM applications typically use a middleware to even out the differences among various platforms.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] With the onset of Windows operating systems and XFS on ATMs, the software applications have the ability to become more intelligent.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This has created a new breed of ATM applications commonly referred to as programmable applications.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] These types of applications allow for an entirely new host of applications in which the ATM terminal can do more than only communicate with the ATM switch.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] It is now empowered to connect to other content servers and video banking systems.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Notable ATM software that operates on XFS platforms include Triton PRISM, Diebold Agilis EmPower, NCR APTRA Edge, Absolute Systems AbsoluteINTERACT, KAL Kalignite Software Platform, Phoenix Interactive VISTAatm, Wincor Nixdorf ProTopas, Euronet EFTS and Intertech inter-ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] With the move of ATMs to industry-standard computing environments, concern has risen about the integrity of the ATM's software stack.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The number of tellers in the United States increased from approximately 300,000 in 1970 to approximately 600,000 in 2010.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A contributing factor may have been the introduction of automated teller machines.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs allow a branch to operate with fewer tellers, making it more economical for banks to open more branches, necessitating more tellers to staff those additional branches.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Further automation and online banking, however, may reverse this increase resulting in a trend toward fewer bank teller positions.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs also provide a practical demonstration of a number of security systems and concepts operating together and how various security concerns are addressed.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Early ATM security focused on making the terminals invulnerable to physical attack; they were effectively safes with dispenser mechanisms.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A number of attacks resulted, with thieves attempting to steal entire machines by ram-raiding.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Since the late 1990s, criminal groups operating in Japan improved ram-raiding by stealing and using a truck loaded with heavy construction machinery to effectively demolish or uproot an entire ATM and any housing to steal its cash.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Another attack method, *plofkraak* (a Dutch term), is to seal all openings of the ATM with silicone and fill the vault with a combustible gas or to place an explosive inside, attached, or near the machine.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This gas or explosive is ignited and the vault is opened or distorted by the force of the resulting explosion and the criminals can break in.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATM bombings began in the Netherlands, but as the nation reduced the number of machines in the country from 20000 to 5000 and discouraged cash use, the mostly Moroccan-Dutch gangs expert in the attacks moved elsewhere.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Such theft has also occurred in Belgium, France, Denmark, Germany, Australia, and the United Kingdom.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] When anti-gas explosion prevention devices and reinforced ATMs were installed, criminals began using leaf blowers to remove smoke, and more powerful solid explosives.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Despite German banks spending more than €300 million on additional security, the Federal Criminal Police Office estimated that as of 2024 60% of attacks on ATMs in the country succeeded.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Several attacks in the UK (at least one of which was successful) have involved digging a concealed tunnel under the ATM and cutting through the reinforced base to remove the money.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Modern ATM physical security, per other modern money-handling security, concentrates on denying the use of the money inside the machine to a thief by using different types of intelligent banknote neutralization systems (IBNS).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A common method is to simply rob the staff filling the machine with money.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] To avoid this, the schedule for filling them is kept secret, varying and random.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The money is often kept in cassettes, which will dye the money if incorrectly opened.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The security of ATM transactions relies mostly on the integrity of the secure cryptoprocessor: the ATM often uses general commodity components that sometimes are not considered to be "trusted systems".
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Encryption of personal information, required by law in many jurisdictions, is used to prevent fraud.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Sensitive data in ATM transactions are usually encrypted with DES, but transaction processors now usually require the use of Triple DES.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Remote Key Loading techniques may be used to ensure the secrecy of the initialization of the encryption keys in the ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Message Authentication Code (MAC) or Partial MAC may also be used to ensure messages have not been tampered with while in transit between the ATM and the financial network.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] There have also been a number of incidents of fraud by man-in-the-middle attacks, where criminals have attached fake keypads or card readers to existing machines.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] These have then been used to record customers' PINs and bank card information in order to gain unauthorized access to their accounts.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Various ATM manufacturers have put in place countermeasures to protect the equipment they manufacture from these threats.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Alternative methods to verify cardholder identities have been tested and deployed in some countries, such as finger and palm vein patterns, iris, and facial recognition technologies.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Cheaper mass-produced equipment has been developed and is being installed in machines globally that detect the presence of foreign objects on the front of ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Current tests have shown 99% detection success for all types of skimming devices.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Openings on the customer side of ATMs are often covered by mechanical shutters to prevent tampering with the mechanisms when they are not in use.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Alarm sensors are placed inside ATMs and their servicing areas to alert their operators when doors have been opened by unauthorized personnel.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] To protect against hackers, ATMs have a built-in firewall.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Once the firewall has detected malicious attempts to break into the machine remotely, the firewall locks down the machine.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Rules are usually set by the government or ATM operating body that dictate what happens when integrity systems fail.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Customers often commented that it is difficult to recover money lost in this way, but this is often complicated by the policies regarding suspicious activities typical of the criminal element.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In some countries, multiple security cameras and security guards are a common feature.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The New York State Comptroller's Office has advised the New York State Department of Banking to have more thorough safety inspections of ATMs in high crime areas.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Consultants of ATM operators assert that the issue of customer security should have more focus by the banking industry; it has been suggested that efforts are now more concentrated on the preventive measure of deterrent legislation than on the problem of ongoing forced withdrawals.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] At least as far back as 30 July 1986, consultants of the industry have advised for the adoption of an emergency PIN system for ATMs, where the user can send a silent alarm in response to a threat.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Legislative efforts to require an emergency PIN system have appeared in Illinois, Kansas and Georgia, but none has succeeded yet.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In January 2009, Senate Bill 1355 was proposed in the Illinois Senate that revisits the issue of the reverse emergency PIN system.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The bill is again supported by the police and opposed by the banking lobby.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In 1998, three towns outside Cleveland, Ohio, in response to an ATM crime wave, adopted legislation requiring that an emergency telephone number switch be installed at all outdoor ATMs within their jurisdiction.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In the wake of a homicide in Sharon Hill, Pennsylvania, the city council passed an ATM security bill as well.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In China and elsewhere, many efforts to promote security have been made.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] On-premises ATMs are often located inside the bank's lobby, which may be accessible 24 hours a day.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] These lobbies have extensive security camera coverage, a courtesy telephone for consulting with the bank staff, and a security guard on the premises.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Bank lobbies that are not guarded 24 hours a day may also have secure doors that can only be opened from outside by swiping the bank card against a wall-mounted scanner, allowing the bank to identify which card enters the building.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Most ATMs will also display on-screen safety warnings and may also be fitted with convex mirrors above the display allowing the user to see what is happening behind them.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] As of 2013, the only claim available about the extent of ATM-connected homicides is that they range from 500 to 1,000 per year in the US, covering only cases where the victim had an ATM card and the card was used by the killer after the known time of death.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The term *jackpotting* is used to describe one method criminals utilize to steal money from an ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The thieves gain physical access through a small hole drilled in the machine.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] They disconnect the existing hard drive and connect an external drive using an industrial endoscope.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] They then depress an internal button that reboots the device so that it is now under the control of the external drive.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] They can then have the ATM dispense all of its cash.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In recent years, many ATMs also encrypt the hard disk.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This means that actually creating the software for jackpotting is more difficult, and provides more security for the ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Increasingly, banks are seeking to use the ATM as a sales device to deliver pre approved loans and targeted advertising using products such as ITM (the Intelligent Teller Machine) from Aptra Relate from NCR.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Videoconferencing teller machines are currently referred to as Interactive Teller Machines.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Benton Smith writes in the Idaho Business Review, "The software that allows interactive teller machines to function was created by a Salt Lake City-based company called uGenius, a producer of video banking software.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Before an ATM is placed in a public place, it typically has undergone extensive testing with both test money and the backend computer systems that allow it to perform transactions.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Banking customers also have come to expect high reliability in their ATMs, which provides incentives to ATM providers to minimize machine and network failures.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Financial consequences of incorrect machine operation also provide high degrees of incentive to minimize malfunctions.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATMs and the supporting electronic financial networks are generally very reliable, with industry benchmarks typically producing 98.25% customer availability for ATMs and up to 99.999% availability for host systems that manage the networks of ATMs.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] If ATM networks do go out of service, customers could be left without the ability to make transactions until the beginning of their bank's next time of opening hours.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This said, not all errors are to the detriment of customers; there have been cases of machines giving out money without debiting the account, or giving out higher-value notes as a result of incorrect denomination of banknote being loaded in the money cassettes.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The result of receiving too much money may be influenced by the cardholder agreement in place between the customer and the bank.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Errors that can occur may be mechanical (such as card transport mechanisms; keypads; hard disk failures; envelope deposit mechanisms); software (such as operating system; device driver; application); communications; or purely down to operator error.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] To aid in reliability, some ATMs print each transaction to a roll-paper journal that is stored inside the ATM, which allows its users and the related financial institutions to settle things based on the records in the journal in case there is a dispute.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In some cases, transactions are posted to an electronic journal to remove the cost of supplying journal paper to the ATM and for more convenient searching of data.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Improper money checking can cause the possibility of a customer receiving counterfeit banknotes from an ATM.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Some ATMs may be stocked and wholly owned by outside companies, which can further complicate this problem.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Bill validation technology can be used by ATM providers to help ensure the authenticity of the cash before it is stocked in the machine; those with cash recycling capabilities include this capability.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Banks are also liable to pay the late fees in case of delay in repayment of funds post seven days.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] As with any device containing objects of value, ATMs and the systems they depend on to function are the targets of fraud.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Fraud against ATMs and people's attempts to use them takes several forms.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The first known instance of a fake ATM was installed at a shopping mall in Manchester, Connecticut, in 1993.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] By modifying the inner workings of a Fujitsu model 7020 ATM, a criminal gang known as the Bucklands Boys stole information from cards inserted into the machine by customers.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This type of scam was featured on the TV series *The Real Hustle*.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] ATM behavior can change during what is called "stand-in" time, where the bank's cash dispensing network is unable to access databases that contain account information (possibly for database maintenance).
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In an attempt to prevent criminals from shoulder surfing the customer's personal identification number (PIN), some banks draw privacy areas on the floor.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] For a low-tech form of fraud, the easiest is to simply steal a customer's card along with its PIN.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A later variant of this approach is to trap the card inside of the ATM's card reader with a device often referred to as a Lebanese loop.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] When the customer gets frustrated by not getting the card back and walks away from the machine, the criminal is able to remove the card and withdraw cash from the customer's account, using the card and its PIN.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Although somewhat replaced in terms of volume by skimming incidents, a re-emergence of card trapping has been noticed in regions such as Europe, where EMV chip and PIN cards have increased in circulation.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Another simple form of fraud involves attempting to get the customer's bank to issue a new card and its PIN and stealing them from their mail.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Card data is then cloned into a duplicate card and the criminal attempts a standard cash withdrawal.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The availability of low-cost commodity wireless cameras, keypads, card readers, and card writers has made it a relatively simple form of fraud, with comparatively low risk to the fraudsters.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In an attempt to stop these practices, countermeasures against card cloning have been developed by the banking industry, in particular by the use of smart cards which cannot easily be copied or spoofed by unauthenticated devices, and by attempting to make the outside of their ATMs tamper evident.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Older chip-card security systems include the French Carte Bleue, Visa Cash, Mondex, Blue from American Express and EMV '96 or EMV 3.11.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The most actively developed form of smart card security in the industry today is known as EMV 2000 or EMV 4.x.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] EMV is widely used in the UK (Chip and PIN) and other parts of Europe, but when it is not available in a specific area, ATMs must fall back to using the easy–to–copy magnetic stripe to perform transactions.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This fallback behavior can be exploited.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] However, the fallback option has been removed on the ATMs of some UK banks, meaning if the chip is not read, the transaction will be declined.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Card cloning and skimming can be detected by the implementation of magnetic card reader heads and firmware that can read a signature embedded in all magnetic stripes during the card production process.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] This signature, known as a "MagnePrint" or "BluPrint", can be used in conjunction with common two-factor authentication schemes used in ATM, debit/retail point-of-sale and prepaid card applications.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The concept and various methods of copying the contents of an ATM card's magnetic stripe onto a duplicate card to access other people's financial information were well known in the hacking communities by late 1990.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] After getting all the information from the videotapes, he was able to produce clone cards which not only allowed him to withdraw the full daily limit for each account, but also allowed him to sidestep withdrawal limits by using multiple copied cards.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] In court, it was shown that he could withdraw as much as £10,000 per hour by using this method.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Stone was sentenced to five years and six months in prison.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A talking ATM is a type of ATM that provides audible instructions so that people who cannot read a screen can independently use the machine, therefore effectively eliminating the need for assistance from an external, potentially malevolent source.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] All audible information is delivered privately through a standard headphone jack on the face of the machine.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Alternatively, some banks such as the Nordea and Swedbank use a built-in external speaker which may be invoked by pressing the talk button on the keypad.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Information is delivered to the customer either through pre-recorded sound files or via text-to-speech speech synthesis.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A postal interactive kiosk may share many components of an ATM (including a vault), but it only dispenses items related to postage.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A **scrip cash dispenser** or **cashless ATM** may have many components in common with an ATM, but it cannot dispense physical cash and consequently requires no vault.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Instead, the customer requests a withdrawal transaction from the machine, which prints a receipt or scrip.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] The customer then takes this receipt to a nearby sales clerk, who then exchanges it for cash from the till.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A teller assist unit (TAU) is distinct in that it is designed to be operated solely by trained personnel and not by the general public, integrates directly into interbank networks, and usually is controlled by a computer that is not directly integrated into the overall construction of the unit.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] A Web ATM is an online interface for ATM card banking that uses a smart card reader.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] All the usual ATM functions are available, except for withdrawing cash.
[src:ram-raiding/automated-teller-machine] Most banks in Taiwan provide these online services.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] While chartered as an English settlement in 1613, the town's early growth was driven by an influx of Scottish Presbyterians.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Their descendants' disaffection with Ireland's Anglican establishment contributed to the rebellion of 1798 and to the 1801 union with Great Britain that followed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Access to British capital and markets was transformative.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] When granted city status in 1888, Belfast was the world's largest centre of linen manufacture, and by the 1900s its shipyards were building up to a quarter of all United Kingdom tonnage.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] New industry, which drew large numbers of Catholics from rural districts, was accompanied by growing sectarian tensions in what had been a largely Protestant town.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] A legacy of conflict is the barrier-reinforced separation of Protestant and Catholic working-class districts.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since the Good Friday Agreement, the electoral balance in the once Unionist-controlled city has shifted, albeit with no overall majority, in favour of Irish nationalists.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] New immigrants are adding to the growing number of residents unwilling to identify with either of the two communal traditions.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast has seen significant services sector growth, with important contributions from financial technology (fintech), tourism and, with facilities in the redeveloped Harbour Estate, film.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It retains a port with commercial and industrial docks, including a reduced Harland & Wolff shipyard and aerospace and defence contractors.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Under the Windsor Framework, Belfast and Northern Ireland effectively remain, post Brexit, within both the British domestic, and European Single Market, trading areas for goods.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The city is served by two airports: Belfast City Airport, located on the Lough shore, and Belfast International Airport (also known as Aldergrove), located 15 miles (24 kilometres) west of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast supports two universities: Ulster University in the city centre, and in the Botanic area in the south of the city, Queen's University Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since 2021, Belfast has been a UNESCO designated City of Music.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The name Belfast derives from the Irish *Béal Feirste* (Irish pronunciation: [bʲeːlˠ ˈfʲɛɾˠ(ə)ʃtʲə]), "Mouth of the Farset", a river whose name comes from Irish *fearsaid,* meaning a sandbar or tidal ford.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This was formed where the Farset flowed into the Lagan, along what is now High Street, until culverted in the late 18th century.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It was at this crossing, under or near the current Queen's Bridge, that the early settlement developed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] As a legacy of emigration, Belfast has lent its name to more than a dozen settlements in the United States, of which the largest is Belfast, Maine, and to one each in Australia, Canada, New Zealand and South Africa.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The site of Belfast has been occupied since the Bronze Age.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Giant's Ring, a 5,000-year-old henge, is located near the city, and the remains of Iron Age hill forts can still be seen in the surrounding hills.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] At the beginning of the 14th century, Papal tax rolls record two churches: the "Chapel of Dundela" at Knock (Irish: *cnoc*, meaning "hill") in the east, connected by some accounts to the 7th-century evangelist St.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Colmcille,and, the "Chapel of the Ford", which may have been a successor to a much older parish church on the present Shankill *(Seanchill*, "Old Church") Road, dating back to the 9th, and possibly to St.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the late 12th century, the Normans established a settlement at the ford comprising a parish church (now St.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It was repeatedly taken, demolished, and rebuilt until, at the end of the 16th century, the scorched- earth Nine Years' War broke the remaining Irish power, the O'Neills.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With a commission from King James VI, in 1613 Sir Arthur Chichester undertook the Plantation of Belfast and the surrounding area, building a new castle in what is now Castle Place, and attracting mainly English and Manx settlers.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The subsequent arrival of Scottish Presbyterians embroiled Belfast in its only recorded siege: denounced from London by John Milton as "ungrateful and treacherous guests", in 1649 the newcomers were temporarily expelled by an English Parliamentarian army.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1689, Catholic Jacobite forces, briefly in command of the town, abandoned it in advance of the landing at Carrickfergus of William, Prince of Orange, who proceeded through Belfast to his celebrated victory on 12 July 1690 at the Boyne.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Together with French Huguenots, the Scots introduced the production of linen, a flax-spinning industry that in the 18th century carried Belfast trade to the Americas.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Fortunes were made carrying rough linen clothing and salted provisions to the slave plantations of the West Indies; sugar and rum to Baltimore and New York City; and for the return to Belfast flaxseed and tobacco from the colonies.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From the 1760s, profits from the trade financed improvements in the town's commercial infrastructure, including the Lagan Canal, new docks and quays, and the construction of the White Linen Hall which together attracted to Belfast the linen trade that had formerly gone through Dublin.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Abolitionist sentiment, however, defeated the proposal of the greatest of the merchant houses, Cunningham and Greg, in 1786 to commission ships for the Middle Passage.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] As "Dissenters" from the established Anglican church (with its episcopacy and ritual), Presbyterians were conscious of sharing, if only in part, the disabilities of Ireland's dispossessed Roman Catholic majority; and of being denied representation in the Irish Parliament.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast's two MPs remained nominees of the Chichesters (Marquesses of Donegall).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With their emigrant kinsmen in America, the region's Presbyterians were to share a growing disaffection from the Crown.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] When early in the American War of Independence, Belfast Lough was raided by the privateer John Paul Jones, the townspeople assembled their own Volunteer militia.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Formed ostensibly for defence of the Kingdom, Volunteer corps were soon pressing their own protest against "taxation without representation".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Further emboldened by the French Revolution, a more radical element in the town, the Society of United Irishmen, called for Catholic emancipation and a representative national government.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In hopes of French assistance, in 1798 the Society organised a republican insurrection.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The rebel tradesmen and tenant farmers were defeated north of the town at the Battle of Antrim and to the south at the Battle of Ballynahinch.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Britain seized on the rebellion to abolish the Irish Parliament, unlamented in Belfast, and to incorporate Ireland in a United Kingdom.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1832, British parliamentary reform permitted the town its first electoral contest – an occasion for an early and lethal sectarian riot.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] While other Irish towns experienced a loss of manufacturing, from the 1820s Belfast underwent rapid industrial expansion.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] After a cotton boom and bust, the town emerged as the global leader in the production of linen goods (mill, and finishing, work largely employing women and children), winning the moniker "Linenopolis".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Shipbuilding led the development of heavier industry.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] By the 1900s, her shipyards were building up to a quarter of the total United Kingdom tonnage, and on the eve of the First World War, in 1914, close one eighth of world production.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This included from the yard of Harland & Wolff the ill-fated RMS *Titanic,* at the time of her launch in 1911 the largest ship afloat.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Other major export industries included textile machinery, rope-making, tobacco and mineral waters.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Industry drew in a new Catholic population settling largely in the west of the town—refugees from a rural poverty intensified by Belfast's mechanisation of spinning and weaving and, in the 1840s, by famine.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The plentiful supply of cheap labour helped attract English and Scottish capital to Belfast, but it was also a cause of insecurity.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Protestant workers organised and dominated the apprenticed trades and gave a new lease of life to the once largely rural Orange Order.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Sectarian tensions, which frequently broke out in riots and workplace expulsions, were also driven by the "constitutional question": the prospect of a restored Irish parliament in which Protestants (and northern industry) feared being a minority interest.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] On 28 September 1912, unionists massed at Belfast's City Hall to sign the Ulster Covenant, pledging to use "all means which may be found necessary to defeat the present conspiracy to set up a Home Rule Parliament in Ireland".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This was followed, in a prelude to partition, by the drilling and eventual arming of a 100,000-strong Ulster Volunteer Force (UVF).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The immediate crisis was averted by the onset of World War I.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The UVF formed the 36th (Ulster) Division whose sacrifices in the Battle of the Somme continue to be commemorated in the city by unionist and loyalist organisations.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1920–22, as it emerged as the capital of the six counties remaining in United Kingdom, the city witnessed "savage and unprecedented" communal violence.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With Catholics the principal victims, "fire, plunder, and assault" drove 10,000 people from the city, and took 500 lives (a higher toll per capita than the War of Independence and Civil War were to cause in Dublin).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The lines drawn saw off the challenge to "unionist unity" posed by labour.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Industry had been paralysed by strikes in 1907 and again in 1919 (when the city was effectively policed by strikers).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Until "troubles" returned at the end of the 1960s, it was not uncommon in Belfast for the Ulster Unionist Party to have its council and parliamentary candidates returned unopposed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1932, the opening of the new buildings for Northern Ireland's devolved Parliament at Stormont was overshadowed by the protests of the unemployed and ten days of running street battles with the police.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The government conceded increases in Outdoor Relief, but labour unity was short lived.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1935, celebrations of King George V's Jubilee and of the annual Twelfth were followed by renewed riots and workplace expulsions, a sectarian logic that extended itself to the interpretation of darkening events in Europe.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Labour candidates found support for the anti-clerical Spanish Republic (marked today by a *No Pasaran!* stained glass window in City Hall) characterised as another instance of No-Popery.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1938, nearly a third of industrial workers were unemployed, malnutrition was a major issue, and at 9.6% the city's infant mortality rate (compared with 5.9% in Sheffield, England) was among the highest in United Kingdom.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the spring of 1941, the German *Luftwaffe* appeared four times over Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In addition to the shipyards and the Short & Harland aircraft factory, the Belfast Blitz severely damaged or destroyed more than half the city's housing stock, and devastated the old town centre around High Street.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the greatest loss of life in any air raid outside of London, more than a thousand people were killed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] At the same time, a British-funded welfare state "revolutionised access" to education and health care.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The resulting rise in expectations; together with the uncertainty caused by the decline of the city's Victorian-era industries, contributed to growing protest, and counter protest, in the 1960s over the Unionist government's record on civil and political rights.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] For reasons that nationalists and unionists dispute, the public protests of the late 1960s soon gave way to communal violence (in which as many as 60,000 people were intimidated from their homes) and to loyalist and republican paramilitarism.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Introduced onto the streets in August 1969, the British Army committed to the longest continuous deployment in its history, Operation Banner.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Beginning in 1970 with the Falls curfew, and followed in 1971 by internment, this included counterinsurgency measures directed chiefly at the Provisional Irish Republican Army.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The PIRA characterised their operations, including the bombing of Belfast's commercial centre, as a struggle against British occupation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Preceded by loyalist and republican ceasefires, the 1998 "Good Friday" Belfast Agreement returned a new power-sharing legislative assembly and executive to Stormont.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the intervening years in Belfast, some 20,000 people had been injured, and 1,500 killed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Eighty-five percent of the conflict-related deaths had occurred within 1,000 metres of the communal interfaces, largely in the north and west of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The security barriers erected at these interfaces are an enduring physical legacy of the Troubles.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The 14 neighbourhoods they separate are among the 20 most deprived wards in Northern Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In May 2013, the Northern Ireland Executive committed to the removal of all peace lines by mutual consent.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The target date of 2023 was passed with only a small number dismantled.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The more affluent districts escaped the worst of the violence, but the city centre was a major target.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This was especially so during the first phase of the PIRA campaign in the early 1970s, when the organisation hoped to secure quick political results through maximum destruction.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Including car bombs and incendiaries, between 1969 and 1977 the city experienced 2,280 explosions.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In addition to the death and injury caused, they accelerated the loss of the city's Victorian fabric.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since the turn of the century, the loss of employment and population in the city centre has been reversed.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This reflects the growth of the service economy, for which a new district has been developed on former dockland, the Titanic Quarter.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The growing tourism sector lists as attractions the murals and peace walls that echo the violence of the past.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In recent years, "Troubles tourism" has presented visitors with new territorial markers: flags, murals and graffiti in which loyalists and republicans take opposing sides in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1997, unionists lost overall control of Belfast City Council for the first time in its history.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The election in 2011 saw Irish nationalist councillors outnumber unionist councillors, with Sinn Féin becoming the largest party, and the cross-community Alliance Party holding the balance of power.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the 2016 Brexit referendum, Belfast's four parliamentary constituencies returned a substantial majority (60 percent) for remaining within the European Union, as did Northern Ireland as a whole (55.8), the only UK region outside London and Scotland to do so.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In February 2022, the Democratic Unionist Party, which had actively campaigned for Brexit, withdrew from the power-sharing executive and collapsed the Stormont institutions to protest the 2020 UK-EU Northern Ireland Protocol.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With the promise of equal access to the British and European markets, this designates Belfast as a point of entry to the European Single Market within whose regulatory framework local producers will continue to operate.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] After two years, the standoff was resolved with an agreement to eliminate routine checks on UK-destined goods.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast is at the mouth of the River Lagan at the head of Belfast Lough open through the North Channel to the Irish Sea and to the North Atlantic.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the course of the 19th century, the location's estuarine features were re-engineered.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With dredging and reclamation, the lough was made to accommodate a deep sea port, and extensive shipyards.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It remains the case that much of the city centre is built on an estuarine bed of "sleech": silt, peat, mud and—a source the city's ubiquitous red brick— soft clay, that presents a challenge for high-rise construction.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The city centre is also subject to tidal flood risk.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Rising sea levels could mean, that without significant investment, flooding in the coming decades will be persistent.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The city is overlooked on the County Antrim side (to the north and northwest) by a precipitous basalt escarpment—the near continuous line of Divis Mountain (478 m), Black Mountain (389 m) and Cavehill (368 m)—whose "heathery slopes and hanging fields are visible from almost any part of the city".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From County Down side (on the south and south east) it is flanked by the lower-lying Castlereagh and Hollywood hills.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The sand and gravel Malone Ridge extends up river to the south-west.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From 1820, Belfast began to spread rapidly beyond its 18th century limits.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] To the north, it stretched out along roads which drew into the town migrants from Scots-settled hinterland of County Antrim.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Largely Presbyterian, they enveloped a number of Catholic-occupied "mill-row" clusters: New Lodge, Ardoyne and "the Marrowbone".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Together with areas of more substantial housing in the Oldpark district, these are wedged between Protestant working-class housing stretching from Tiger's Bay out the Shore Road on one side, and up the Shankill (the original Antrim Road) on the other.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] These include Cupar Way where tourists are informed that, at 45 feet, the barrier is "three times higher than the Berlin Wall and has been in place for twice as long".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] With other working-class districts, Shankill suffered from the "collapse of old industrial Belfast".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] But it was also greatly affected from the 1960s by the city's most ambitious programme of "slum clearance".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Red-brick, "two up, two down" terraced streets, typical of 19th century working-class housing, were replaced with flats, maisonettes, and car parks but few facilities.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In a period of twenty years, due largely to redevelopment, 50,000 residents left the area leaving an aging population of 26,000 and more than 100 acres of wasteland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Meanwhile, road schemes, including the terminus of the M1 motorway and the Westlink, demolished a mixed dockland community, Sailortown, and severed the streets linking the Shankill area and the rest of both north and west Belfast to the city centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] New "green field" housing estates were built on the outer edges of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The onset of the Troubles overwhelmed attempts to promote these as "mixed" neighbourhoods so that the largest of these developments on the city's northern edge, Rathcoole, rapidly solidified as a loyalist community.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 2004, it was estimated that 98% of public housing in Belfast was divided along religious lines.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Among the principal landmarks of north Belfast are the Crumlin Road Gaol (1845) now a major visitor attraction, Belfast Royal Academy (1785) - the oldest school in the city, St Malachy's College (1833), Holy Cross Church, Ardoyne (1902), Waterworks Park (1889), and Belfast Zoo (1934).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the mid-19th century rural poverty and famine drove large numbers of Catholic tenant farmers, landless labourers and their families toward Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Their route brought them down the Falls Road and into what are now remnants of an older Catholic enclave around St Mary's Church, the town's first Catholic chapel (opened in 1784 with Presbyterian subscriptions), and Smithfield Market.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Reflecting the nature of available employment as mill workers, domestics and shop assistants, the population, initially, was disproportionately female.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Further opportunities for women on the Falls Road arose through developments in education and public health.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1900, the Dominican Order opened St Mary's [Teacher] Training College, and in 1903 King Edward VII opened the Royal Victoria Hospital at the junction with the Grosvenor Road.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Extensively redeveloped and expanded, the hospital has a staff of more than 8,500.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The area's greatest visitor attractions are its wall and gable-end murals.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In contrast to those in loyalist areas, where Israel is typically the only outside reference, these range more freely beyond the local conflict frequently expressing solidarity with Palestinians, with Cuba, and with Basque and Catalan separatists.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] West Belfast is separated from South Belfast, and from the otherwise abutting loyalist districts of Sandy Row and the Donegall Road, by rail lines, the M1 Motorway (to Dublin and the west); industrial and retail parks, and the remnants of the Blackstaff (Owenvarra) bog meadows.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast began stretching up-river in the 1840s and 50s: out the Ormeau and Lisburn roads and, between them, running along a ridge of higher ground, the Malone Road.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From "leafy" avenues of increasingly substantial (and in the course of time "mixed") housing, the Upper Malone broadened out into areas of parkland and villas.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Further out still, where they did not survive as public parks, from the 1960s the great-house demesnes of the city's former mill-owners and industrialists were developed for public housing: loyalist estates such as Seymour Hill and Belvoir.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Meanwhile, in Malone and along the river embankments, new houses and apartment blocks have been squeezed in, increasing the general housing density.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Beyond the Queen's University area the area's principal landmarks are the 15-storey tower block of Belfast City Hospital (1986) on the Lisburn Road, and the Lagan Valley Regional Park through which a towpath extends from the City-centre quayside to Lisburn.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Northern Ireland's three permanent diplomatic missions are situated on the Malone Road, the consulates of China, Poland and the United States.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The first district on the right bank of the Lagan (the County Down side) to be incorporated in Belfast was Ballymacarrett in 1853.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Harland & Wolff, whose gantry cranes, Samson & Goliath, tower over the area, was long the mainstay of employment — although less securely so for the townland's Catholics (In 1970, when the yard still had a workforce of 10,000, only 400 Catholics were employed).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Tolerated in periods of expansion as navvies and casual labourers, Catholics concentrated in a small enclave, the Short Strand, which has continued into this century to feature as a sectarian flashpoint.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Home to around 2,500 people, it is the only distinctly nationalist area in the east of the river.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] East Belfast developed from the Queens Bridge (1843), through Ballymacarrett, east along the Newtownards Road and north (along the east shore of the Lough) up the Holywood Road; and from the Albert Bridge (1890) south east out the Cregagh and Castlereagh roads.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The further out, the more substantial, and less religiously segregated, the housing until again encountering the city's outer ring of public housing estates: loyalist Knocknagoney, Lisnasharragh, and Tullycarnet.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This century, efforts have been made to add to East Belfast's two obvious visitor attractions: Samson & Goliath (the "banana yellow" Harland & Wolff cranes date only from the early 1970s) and the Parliament Buildings at Stormont.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 2015, the Orange Order opened the Museum of Orange Heritage on the Cregagh Road with the aim of educating the wider public about "the origins, traditions and continued relevance" of the parading institution.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This embraces "the Markets", the one remaining inner-city area of housing.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Of the various markets, including those for the sale and shipping of livestock, from which it derives its name, only one survives, the former produce market, St George's Market, now a food and craft market popular with visitors to the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The oldest public building in Belfast, Clifton House (1771–74), the Belfast Charitable Society poorhouse, is on North Queen Street.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It is now partly cut off from the city centre by arterial roads.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In addition there are small sets of city-centre Georgian terraces.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Of the much larger Victorian city a substantial legacy has survived the Blitz, The Troubles and planning and development.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Patrick's Catholic Church in Donegall Street (1877).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Baroque revival City Hall was finished in 1906 on the site of the former White Linen Hall, and was built to reflect Belfast's city status, granted by Queen Victoria in 1888.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Its Edwardian design influenced the Victoria Memorial in Calcutta, India, and Durban City Hall in South Africa.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The dome is 173 ft (53 m) high and figures above the door state "Hibernia encouraging and promoting the Commerce and Arts of the City".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Across from the City Hall, on Donegall Sq.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] West, is the Renaissance and Baroque revival Scottish Provident Institution (1902).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] On the east side, a branch of the Ulster Bank is built behind the classical portico of a former Methodist church dating from 1846.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] On the north side, facing the City Hall is the once palatial, copper-domed, "Royal Irish Linen Warehouse" of Robinson & Cleaver (1888), until its closure in 1984, the city's premier department store.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Next door, its successor, Marks and Spencers, is housed behind the red sandstone, Florentine Gothic, facade (1869) of a rival linen business that was burned out in the Blitz.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Built in the Romanesque-style on the site of an earlier neo-classical church, St Anne's Church of Ireland Cathedral was consecrated in 1904.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The north transept, featuring on its exterior "the largest Celtic cross in Ireland", was completed in 1981.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In view of its unstable foundation in estuarine sleech, plans for a bell tower were abandoned in favour of a 40-metre stainless steel "Spire of Hope" installed in 2007.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The neoclassical Royal Courts of Justice were opened on Oxford Street in 1933.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The opening Victoria Square Shopping Centre in 2008 was to symbolise the rebound of the city centre since its days as a restricted security zone during the Troubles.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] But retail footfall in the centre is limited by competition with out-of-town shopping centres and with internet retailing.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] As of November 2023, footfall had not recovered pre-COVID pandemic levels.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] There are compensating trends: the growth in tourism and hospitality which has included a sustained boom in hotel construction.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The City Council also talks of a "residential-led regeneration".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] New townhouse and apartments schemes are being developed for the city's quays, and for Titanic Quarter.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] People can be found sleeping rough on the streets of the city centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Numbers, while growing, may be comparatively small for a city of its size in the British Isles.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 2022, counts and estimates by the Northern Ireland Housing Executive identified a total of 26 rough sleepers in Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] This is against a background (in 2023) of 2,317 people (0.67% of residents) presenting as homeless, many of whom are in temporary accommodation and shelters.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Such figures, however, do not include all those living in severely overcrowded conditions, involuntarily sharing with other households on a long-term basis, or sleeping rough in hidden locations.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since 2001, buoyed by increasing numbers of tourists, the city council has promoted a number of cultural quarters.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It hosts a yearly visual and performing arts festival.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The adjoining Custom House Square is one of the city's main outdoor venues for free concerts and street entertainment.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Without defined geographical boundaries, the Gaeltacht Quarter encompasses Irish-speaking Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] (According to the 2021 census, 15.5% of people in the city have some knowledge of Irish, 4% speak it daily).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It is generally understood as an area around the Falls Road in west Belfast served by the Cultúrlann McAdam Ó Fiaich cultural centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It can be said to include, at the Skainos Centre in unionist east Belfast, Turas, a project that promotes Irish through night classes and cultural events in the belief that "the language belongs to all".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Moving further south along the so-called "Golden Mile" of bars and clubs through Shaftesbury Square, there is the Queen's [University] Quarter.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In addition to the university (spread over 250 buildings, of which 120 are listed as being of architectural merit), it is home to Botanic Gardens and the Ulster Museum.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Finally, the Titanic Quarter covers 0.75 km2 (185 acres) of reclaimed land adjacent to Belfast Harbour, formerly known as *Queen's Island*.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Named after RMS *Titanic*, launched here in 1911, work began in 2003 to transform some former shipyard land into "one of the largest waterfront developments in Europe".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The current area houses *Titanic* Belfast, the Public Records Office of Northern Ireland (PRONI), two hotels, and multiple condo towers and shops, and the Titanic [film] Studios.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From Georgian Belfast, the city retains a civic legacy.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] These remain important cultural venues: in the case of the Gardens, for outdoor festivities including the Belfast Melā, the city's annual August celebration of global cultures.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The two independent cinemas offer their screens for the Belfast Film Festival and the Belfast International Arts Festival.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The principal stage for drama remains the Lyric Theatre (1951, 2011), the largest employer of actors and other theatre professionals in the region.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] At Queens University, drama students stage their productions at the Brian Friel Theatre, a 120-seat studio space (named after the renowned playwright).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In November 2011, Belfast became the smallest city to host the MTV Europe Music Awards.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] A further large-scale venue is the Waterfront Hall, a multi-purpose conference and entertainment centre that first opened in 1997.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The main circular Auditorium seats 2,241 and is modelled on the Berlin Philharmonic Hall.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 2012, the Metropolitan Arts Centre, the "MAC", was opened in the Cathedral Quarter, offering a performance mix of music, theatre, dance and visual art.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Belfast International Tattoo is an annual music and dance event held at the Odyssey Arena, Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Inspired by the tradition of military tattoos, it features performances from pipe bands, military and civilian musicians, dancers, and cultural groups from Northern Ireland and around the world.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Established in 2013, the event aims to showcase Ulster-Scots heritage alongside international acts, attracting large audiences from across the region and beyond.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The city has a number of community arts, and arts education, centres, among them the Crescent Arts Centre in south Belfast, the Irish-language Cultúrlann McAdam Ó Fiaich in west Belfast, The Duncairn in north Belfast and, in the east of the city, EastSide Arts.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Féile an Phobail, a community arts organisation born out of the Internment Commemorations in the west of the city, stages one of the largest community festivals in Europe.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It has grown from its original *August Féile* on the Falls Road, to a year-round programme with a broad range of arts events, talks and discussions.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In November 2021, Belfast became the third city in the British Isles to be designated by UNESCO as City of Music (after Glasgow in 2008 and Liverpool in 2016) and is one of 59 cities worldwide participating in the UNESCO Creative Cities Network.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The greater part of Belfast's music scene is accommodated in the city's pubs and clubs.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Irish traditional music ("trad") is a staple, and is supported, along with Ulster-Scots snare drum and pipe music, by the city's TradFest summer school.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Music offerings also draw on the legacy of the punk and the underground club scene that developed during The Troubles (associated with the groups Stiff Little Fingers and The Undertones, and celebrated in the award-winning 2013 film, Good Vibrations).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Snow Patrol's frontman Gary Lightbody led a line up of private donors that together with public funders established the Oh Yeah music centre in 2008.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Cathedral Quarter non-profit supports young musicians and these have engaged with a range of genres including Alternative rock, Indie rock, Electronica, Post rock, Post punk, Crossover, and Experimental rock.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Queens University hosts the Sonic Arts Research Centre (SARC), an institute for music-based practice and research.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Its purpose designed building, Sonic Laboratory and multichannel studios were opened by Karlheinz Stockhausen, the German composer and "father of electronic music", in 2004.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast is the home of the *Belfast Telegraph*, *Irish News* and, first printed in 1737,*The News Letter*, the oldest English-language daily newspaper in the world still in publication.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The city is the headquarters of BBC Northern Ireland, and ITV station UTV.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Irish public service broadcaster, RTÉ has a studio in the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The national radio station is BBC Radio Ulster with commercial radio stations such as Q Radio, U105, Blast 106 and Irish-language station Raidió Fáilte.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Queen's Radio, a student-run radio station broadcasts from Queen's University Students' Union.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] One of Northern Ireland's two community TV stations, NvTv, is based in the Cathedral Quarter of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Broadcasting only over the Internet is Homely Planet, the Cultural Radio Station for Northern Ireland, supporting community relations.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since the lifting in 1872 of a twenty-year party processions ban, Orange parades in celebration of "the Twelfth" [of July] and the bonfires of the previous evening, the eleventh, have been a fixed fixture of the Belfast calendar.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] While some local feeder and return marches have a history of sectarian disturbance, in recent years, events have generally passed off without serious incident.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The tradition is documented and celebrated in the Museum of Orange Heritage on the Cregagh Road in East Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] What is sometimes referred to as the Catholic equivalent of the Orangemen, the much smaller Ancient Order of Hibernians, confines its parades to nationalist areas in west and north Belfast, as do republicans commemorating the Easter Rising.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In August 1993, in a break with a history of nationalist exclusion from the city centre, a parade marking the introduction of internment in the 1971 proceeded up Royal Avenue toward the City Hall, where it was addressed by Sinn Féin president, Gerry Adams, in front of the statue of Queen Victoria.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Since 1998, the Belfast City Council has funded a city-centre St.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] It is organised by Féile an Phobail as a "carnival" complete with a parade featuring dancers, circus entertainers, floats, and giant puppets.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Critical of what they perceive as an evolving nationalist festival, unionists on the City Council observe that "a lot of the Protestant Unionist Loyalist (PUL) community will stay away from the city centre on St Patrick's Day, the same as some stay away on the Twelfth of July".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 1991, Belfast hosted its first gay pride event.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Belfast Pride, culminating in a city-centre parade at the end of July, is now one of the biggest annual festivals in the city and, according to its organisers, the largest LGBT+ festival in Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The Irish Congress of Trade Unions organises an annual city-centre May Day march and rally.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The International Workers Day has been a public holiday since 1978.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In 2021, there were 345,418 residents within the expanded 2015 Belfast local government boundary and 704,406 for the greater metropolitan area, approximately one third of Northern Ireland's 1.9 million population.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] As with many cities, Belfast's inner city is currently characterised by the elderly, students and single young people, while families tend to live on the periphery.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Socio-economic areas radiate out from the Central Business District, with a pronounced wedge of affluence extending out the Malone Road and Upper Malone Road to the south.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Deprivation levels are notable in the inner parts of the north and the west of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The areas around the Falls Road, Ardoyne and New Lodge (Catholic nationalist) and the Shankill Road (Protestant loyalist) experience some of the highest levels of social deprivation including higher levels of ill health and poor access to services.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] These areas remain firmly segregated, with 80 to 90 percent of residents being of the one religious designation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Consistent with the trend across all of Northern Ireland, the Protestant population within the city has been in decline, while the non-religious, other religious and Catholic population has risen.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The 2021 census recorded the following: 43% of residents as Catholic, 12% as Presbyterian, 8% as Church of Ireland, 3% as Methodist, 6% as belonging to other Christian denominations, 3% to other religions and 24% as having either no religion or no declared religion.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In terms of community background, 47.93% were deemed to belong to, or to have been brought up in, the Catholic faith and 36.45% in a Protestant or other Christian-related denomination.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The comparable figures in 2011 were 48.60% Catholic and 42.28% Protestant or other Christian-related denomination.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Insofar as the city's two indigenous minority languages (Irish and Ulster Scots) are concerned, figures are made available from the decennial UK census.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] On census day, 21 March 2021, 14.93% (43,798) in Belfast claimed to have some knowledge of the Irish language, whilst 5.21% (15,294) claimed to be able to speak, read, write and understand spoken Irish.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] 3.74% (10,963) of residents claimed to use Irish daily and 0.75% (2,192) claimed Irish is their main language.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] 7.17% (21,025) of people in the city claimed to have some knowledge of Ulster Scots, whilst 0.75% (2,207) claimed to be able to speak, read, write and understand spoken Ulster Scots.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] 0.83% (2,430) claimed to use Ulster Scots daily.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] From the mid to late 19th century, there was a community of central European Jews (among its distinguished members, two-time Lord Mayor Otto Jaffe) and of Italians in Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Today, the largest immigrant groups are Poles, Chinese and Indians.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The 2011 census figures recorded a total non-white population of 10,219 or 3.3%, while 18,420 or 6.6% of the population were born outside the UK and Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] Almost half of those born outside the British Isles lived in south Belfast, where they comprised 9.5% of the population.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] The majority of the estimated 5,000 Muslims and 200 Hindu families living in Northern Ireland resided in the Greater Belfast area.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p01] In the 2021 census the percentage of the city's residents born outside the United Kingdom had risen to 9.8.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Services (including retail, health, professional & scientific) account for three quarters of jobs in the Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The balance is in distribution and construction.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In recent years, unemployment has been comparatively low (under 3% in the summer of 2023) for the UK.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] On the other hand, Belfast has a high rate of people economically inactive (close to 30%).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] An early report on the post-Belfast Agreement prospects for the city economy underscored another distinctive feature of its working-age population.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] While it appeared well qualified, with 24 per cent educated to degree level, at "the other end of the educational spectrum", 26 per cent had no qualifications at all, a much higher share than in English cities.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Of Belfast's Victorian-era industry, little remains.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The last working linen factory—Copeland Linens Limited, based in the Shankill area—closed in 2013.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In recent years Harland & Wolff, which at peak production in the Second World War had employed around 35,000 people, has had a workforce of no more than two or three hundred refurbishing oil rigs and fabricating off-shore wind turbines.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] A £1.6 billion Royal Navy contract has offered the yard a new lease, returning it to shipbuilding in 2025, a prospect secured by the purchase of insolvent yard by Spain's state-owned shipbuilder, Navantia.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 1936, Short & Harland Ltd, a joint venture of Short Brothers and Harland & Wolff, began the manufacture of aircraft in the docks area.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 1989, the British government, which had nationalised the company during the Second World War, sold it to the Canadian aerospace company Bombardier.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2020, it was sold on to the American aerostructure company Spirit AeroSystems.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Producing aircraft components, it remains the largest manufacturing concern in Northern Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2025, the Belfast Port and Harbour Estate announced capital projects amounting to than £313m over five years.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] These include a new deepwater quay to accommodate, in addition to larger cruise liners, an expansion the port’s capacity for offshore wind turbine assembly and installation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] From the 1990s, Belfast established itself as a significant location for call centres and for other back-office services.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Attracting U.S. operators such as Citi, Allstate, Liberty Mutual, Aflac and FD Technologies (Kx Systems) and most recently Bank of America, it has since been identified by the UK Treasury as "key fintech [financial technology] hub".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Fintech's key areas (its "ABCD") are artificial intelligence, blockchain, cloud computing, and big data.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The sector's principal constraint, cyber security, has been addressed since 2004 by the Queens University Institute of Electronics, Communications and Information Technology (IECIT), and its Centre for Secure Information Technologies (CSIT).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The IECIT is the anchor tenant at Catalyst (science park) in the Titanic Quarter, which hosts a cluster of cyber-security companies.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Between 2018 and 2023, film and television production based largely in Belfast, and occupying significant new studio capacity in the ports area, contributed £330m to Northern Ireland's economy.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] There are two 8-acre media complexes (serviced by the adjacent City Airport): the Titanic Studios on Queen's Island (the Titanic Quarter) and across the Victoria Channel in Giant's Park on the Lough's north foreshore, the Belfast Harbour Studios.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Together they offer 226,000 ft2 of studio space, plus offices and workshops, and have attracted U.S. production companies such as Amazon, HBO (including all eight series of its fantasy drama *Game of Thrones*), Paramount, Playtone, Universal, and Warner Bros.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] At the beginning of 2024, Ulster University, in partnership with Belfast Harbour and supported by Northern Ireland Screen, announced an £72m investment to add to the complex a new virtual production, research and development, facility, Studio Ulster.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Additional studio space is available at Loop Studios (formerly Britvic) on the Castlereagh Road in East Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In May 2025, Belfast was named "City of Film’"at the Global Production Awards ceremony held during the Cannes Film Festival in France.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Northern Ireland's peace dividend since the 1990s, which includes a marked increase in inward investment, has contributed to a large-scale redevelopment of the city centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Significant projects included Victoria Square, the Cathedral Quarter, Laganside with the Odyssey complex and the landmark Waterfront Hall, the new Titanic Quarter with its *Titanic* Belfast visitor attraction, and the development of the original Short's harbour airfield as Belfast City Airport.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] These developments reflect a boom in tourism (32 million visitors between 2011 and 2018), and related hotel construction.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] This has included an entirely new phenomenon for Belfast: in 1996, the port received its first cruise ship.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2023, Belfast welcomed 153 calls, 8% up from the pre-pandemic record set in 2019.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Ships from 32 different countries landed 320,000 passengers.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] By 2028, there is to be a new a £90 million deep-water quay capable of accommodating the world’s largest cruise liners.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast has also seen growth of "conflict tourism".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] To the dismay of some, "tourists take photos of the division lines that are not consigned to history, but are a part of living Belfast: children play football against the walls that tourists flock to.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The places and the people themselves have become a spectacle, an attraction." Tourist bosses and guides, however, are satisfied that the greater draw is city's other "must-see attractions", and its "convivial food and nightlife scene".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Invest NI, Northern Ireland's economic development agency is pitching Belfast and its hinterland to foreign investors as "only region in the world able to trade goods freely with both GB and EU markets".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Despite the DUP's derailment of devolved government in protest, local business leaders largely welcomed the new trade regime, hailing the promise of dual EU-GB access as a critical opportunity.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Children from Catholic and Protestant homes in Belfast are taught, for the most part, separately on a pattern that, by the mid-nineteenth century, had been established throughout Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Primary and secondary education is divided between (Catholic) Maintained Schools and (non-Catholic/ "Protestant") Controlled Schools.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] They are bound by the same curriculum, but their teaching staff are trained separately (in the university colleges of St Mary's and Stranmillis).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Belfast [later *Royal* Belfast] Academical Institution, opened its doors in 1810 with the intention, in the words of its founder, former United Irishman William Drennan, of being "perfectly unbiased by religious distinctions".
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The principle was not embraced by the town's middle-classes.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In practice, "Inst" provided a grammar education to the town's Presbyterian families while Anglicans favoured the older Royal Belfast Academy (1785); Catholics, St Malachy's diocesan college (1833) and Wesleyans, Methodist College Belfast (1865).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Denominational lines have since blurred, with Catholics in particular moving into the controlled grammars.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] But the presence of 18 selective grammar schools in Belfast is a further feature of post-primary education in Belfast that distinguishes it from that of comparable cities in Great Britain where academic selection was abandoned in the 1960s and 70s.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Partly prompted by the COVID disruption of external testing in 2021/22, some of the city's grammars have begun to review and amend the practice.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It is not clear that this will be on terms that reduce the degree of social segregation they have represented within the system.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2006, the Belfast Education and Library Board became part of the consolidated Education Authority for Northern Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In Belfast, the Authority has responsibility for 156 primary, and 48 secondary schools (including the 18 grammars).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The system is marked by stark inequalities in outcome.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Around 30% of school leavers in the city do not attain 5 GCSEs, A* - C (including Maths and English).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] For those in receipt of free school meals, the figure rises to over 50%.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast Metropolitan College ("Belfast Met") is a further education college with three main campuses around the city, including several smaller buildings.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Formerly known as Belfast Institute of Further and Higher Education, it specialises in vocational education.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The college has over 53,000 students enrolled on full-time and part-time courses, making it one of the largest further education colleges in the UK and the largest in the island of Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Queen's University Belfast was founded as a college in 1845.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 1908, the Catholic bishops lifted their ban on attendance and Queen's was granted university status.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It is a member of the Russell Group, an association of 24 leading research-intensive universities in the UK, and is one of the largest universities in the UK with over 25,000 students – among them over 4,000 international students.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Ulster University, created in its current form in 1984, is a multi-centre university with a campus on the edge of the Cathedral Quarter of Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Since 2021, this original "Arts College" campus has undergone a £1.4bn expansion to accommodate offerings across all departments.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The project promises to bring 15,500 staff and students into the city, and to generate 5,000 new jobs.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast was granted borough status by James VI and I in 1613 and official city status by Queen Victoria in 1888.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Since 1973 it has been a local government district under local administration by Belfast City Council.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast has been represented in the British House of Commons since 1801, and in Northern Ireland Assembly, as presently constituted, since 1998.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast City Council is responsible for a range of powers and services, including land-use and community planning, parks and recreation, building control, arts and cultural heritage.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The city's principal offices are those of the Lord Mayor of Belfast, Deputy Lord Mayor and High Sheriff.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Like other elected positions within the Council such as Committee chairs, these are filled since 1998 using the D'Hondt system so that in recent years the position has rotated between councillors from the three largest factions, Sinn Féin, the Democratic Unionist Party and the Alliance Party.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The first Lord Mayor of Belfast in 1892, Daniel Dixon, like every mayor but one until 1997 (Alliance in 1979), was a unionist.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The first nationalist Lord Mayor of Belfast was Alban Maginness of the Social Democratic and Labour Party (SDLP) in 1997.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The current Lord Mayor is Councillor Róis-Máire Donnelly of Sinn Féin, who has been in the position of Lord Mayor since 1 June 2026.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Her duties include presiding over meetings of the council, receiving distinguished visitors to the city, representing and promoting the city on the national and international stage.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 1997, unionists lost overall control of Belfast City Council for the first time in its history, with the Alliance Party holding the balance of power.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2023, unionists retained just 17 of 60 seats on the council, leaving nationalists (Sinn Féin and the SDLP) just 4 seats short of a majority.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In addition to the 11 Alliance members there are four other councillors, 3 Green and 1 People Before Profit (PBP), who refuse a nationalist/unionist designation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] As Northern Ireland's capital city, Belfast is host to the Northern Ireland Assembly at Stormont, the site of the devolved legislature for Northern Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast is divided into four Northern Ireland Assembly and UK parliamentary constituencies: Belfast North, Belfast West, Belfast South and Mid Down and Belfast East.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] All four extend beyond the city boundaries to include parts of Antrim and Newtownabbey and Lisburn and Castlereagh districts.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In United Kingdom elections, each constituency returns one MP, on a "first past the post" basis to Westminster.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In NI Assembly elections each returns, on the basis of proportional representation, five MLAs to Stormont.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In the Northern Ireland Assembly Elections in 2022, Belfast elected 7 Sinn Féin, 5 DUP, 5 Alliance Party, 1 SDLP, 1 UUP and 1 PBP MLAs.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In the 2017 UK general election, the DUP won all but the Sinn Féin stronghold of Belfast West.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In the 2019 and 2024 UK general elections, they retained only Belfast East, losing Belfast North to Sinn Féin and Belfast South to the SDLP.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Belfast Health & Social Care Trust is one of five trusts that were created on 1 April 2007 by the Department of Health.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast contains most of Northern Ireland's regional specialist centres.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Royal Hospitals site in west Belfast (junction of Grosvenor and Falls roads) contains two hospitals.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Royal Victoria Hospital (its origins in a number of successive institutions, beginning in 1797 with The Belfast Fever Hospital) provides both local and regional services.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Specialist services include cardiac surgery, critical care and the Regional Trauma Centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Children's Hospital (Royal Belfast Hospital for Sick Children) provides general hospital care for children in Belfast and provides most of the paediatric regional specialities.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Belfast City Hospital (evolved from the 1841 Belfast Union Workhouse and infirmary) on the Lisburn Road is the regional specialist centre for haematology and is home to a major cancer centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Mary G McGeown Regional Nephrology Unit at the City Hospital is the kidney transplant centre and provides regional renal services for Northern Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Musgrave Park Hospital (1920) in south Belfast specialises in orthopaedics, rheumatology, sports medicine and rehabilitation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It is home to Northern Ireland's first Acquired Brain Injury Unit.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Mater Hospital (founded in 1883 by the Sisters of Mercy) on the Crumlin Road provides a wide range of services, including acute inpatient, emergency and maternity services, to north Belfast and the surrounding areas.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Ulster Hospital, Upper Newtownards Road, Dundonald, on the eastern edge of the city, first founded as the Ulster Hospital for Women and Sick Children in 1872, is the major acute hospital for the South Eastern Health and Social Care Trust.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It delivers a full range of outpatient, inpatient and daycare medical and surgical services.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast is a relatively car-dependent city by European standards, with an extensive road network including the 22.5 miles (36 km) M2 and M22 motorway route.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Reflecting this high volume of traffic, a 2025 study ranked Belfast as the 15th noisiest city in the United Kingdom.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Black taxis are common in the city, operating on a share basis in some areas.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] These are outnumbered by private hire taxis.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Bus and rail public transport in Northern Ireland is operated by subsidiaries of Translink.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] More distant suburbs are served by Ulsterbus.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Northern Ireland Railways provides suburban services along three lines running through Belfast's northern suburbs to Carrickfergus, Larne and Larne Harbour, eastwards towards Bangor and south-westwards towards Lisburn and Portadown.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] This service is known as the Belfast Suburban Rail system.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast is linked directly to Coleraine, Portrush and Derry.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast has a direct rail connection with Dublin called *Enterprise* operated jointly by NIR and the Irish rail company Iarnród Éireann.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 2024, the city's Europa Bus Centre and Great Victoria Street rail station, was replaced by a new Belfast Grand Central Station.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It is "the largest integrated transport facility on the island of Ireland" with bus stands, railway platforms, and facilities for taxis and bicycles.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The city has two airports: Belfast City Airport, close to the city centre on the eastern shore of Belfast Lough and Belfast International Airport 10 miles (30–40 minutes drive) to the west on the shore of Lough Neagh.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Both operate UK domestic and European flights.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The city is also served by Dublin Airport, two hours to the south, with direct inter-continental connections.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In addition to its extensive freight business, the Belfast Port offers car-ferry sailings, operated by Stena Line, to Cairnryan in Scotland (5 Sailings Daily.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] 2 hours 22 minutes) and to Liverpool-Birkenhead (14 sailings weekly.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Isle of Man Steam Packet Company provides a seasonal connection to Douglas, Isle of Man.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Glider bus service is a new form of transport in Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Introduced in 2018, it is a bus rapid transit system linking East Belfast, West Belfast and the Titanic Quarter from the City Centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Using articulated buses, the £90 million service saw a 17% increase in its first month in Belfast, with 30,000 more people using the Gliders every week.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The service is being recognised as helping to modernise the city's public transport.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] National Cycle Route 9 to Newry, which will eventually connect with Dublin, starts in Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Half of Belfast's water is supplied via the Aquarius pipeline from the Silent Valley Reservoir in County Down, created to collect water from the Mourne Mountains.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The other half is now supplied from Lough Neagh via Dunore Water Treatment Works in County Antrim.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The citizens of Belfast pay for their water in their rates bill.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Plans to bring in additional water tariffs were deferred by devolution in May 2007.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Power is provided from a number of power stations via NIE Networks Limited transmission lines.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] (Just under a half of electricity consumption in Northern Ireland is generated from renewable sources).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Phoenix Natural Gas Ltd. started supplying customers in Larne and Greater Belfast with natural gas in 1996 via the newly constructed Scotland-Northern Ireland pipeline.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Rates in Belfast (and the rest of Northern Ireland) were reformed in April 2007.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The discrete capital value system means rates bills are determined by the capital value of each domestic property as assessed by the Valuation and Lands Agency.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast City Council owns and maintains 17 leisure centres across the city, run on its behalf by the non-profit social enterprise GLL under the 'Better' brand.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The oldest (1828) and one of the most popular parks Botanic Gardens in the Queen's Quarter.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Built in the 1830s and designed by Sir Charles Lanyon, its Palm House is one of the earliest examples of a curvilinear and cast iron glasshouse.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Other attractions in the park include the recently restored Tropical Ravine, a humid jungle glen built in 1889, rose gardens and public events ranging from live opera broadcasts to pop concerts.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The largest municipal park in the city, and closest to the city centre, lies on the right bank of Lagan.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The 100-acres of Ormeau Park were opened to the public in 1871 on what was the last demesne of the town's former proprietors, the Chichesters, Marquesses of Donegall.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In north Belfast, the Waterworks, two reservoirs to which the public have had access since 1897, are features of a park supporting angling and waterfowl.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In 1906, a further water park, Victoria, opened behind industrial dockland on what had been the eastern shore of the Lough.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It is now connected through east Belfast by the Connswater Community Greenway which offers 16 km of continuous cycle and walkway through east Belfast.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Colin Glenn Forest Park, the National Trust Divis and the Black Mountain Ridge Trail, and Cave Hill Country Park. offer panoramic views over Belfast and beyond from the west.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Climbing the Castlereagh Hills, the National Trust Lisnabreeny Cregagh Glen does the same from the east.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Below Cave Hill, the council maintains one of the few local government-funded zoos in the British Isles.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] It carries out important conservation work and takes part in European and international breeding programmes which help to ensure the survival of many species under threat.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast has several notable sports teams playing a diverse variety of sports such as football, Gaelic games, rugby, cricket, and ice hockey.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Belfast Marathon is run annually on May Day, The 41st Marathon in 2023, with related events (Wheelchair Race, Team Relay and 8 Mile Walk) attracted 15,000 participants.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The Northern Ireland national football team plays its home matches at Windsor Park.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Football clubs with stadia and training grounds in the city include: Linfield, Glentoran, Crusaders, Cliftonville, Donegal Celtic, Harland & Wolff Welders, Dundela, Knockbreda, PSNI, Newington, Sport & Leisure and Brantwood.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast is home to over twenty Gaelic football and hurling clubs.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Casement Park in west Belfast, home to the Antrim county teams, had a capacity of 31,500 making it the second largest Gaelic Athletic Association ground in Ulster.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Listed as one of the venues for the UK and Ireland's successful UEFA Euro 2028 bid, with co-funding from the Irish government there are plans for a complete rebuild.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In May 2020, the foundation of East Belfast GAA returned Gaelic Games to East Belfast after decades of its absence in the area.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The current club president is Irish-language enthusiast Linda Ervine who comes from a unionist background in the area.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The team currently plays in the Down Senior County League.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The 1999 Heineken Cup champions Ulster Rugby play at Ravenhill Stadium in the south of the city.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast has four teams in rugby's All-Ireland League: Belfast Harlequins in Division 1B; and Instonians, Queen's University and Malone in Division 2A.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast is home to the Stormont cricket ground since 1949 and was the venue for the Irish cricket team's first ever One Day International against England in 2006.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The 9,500 capacity SSE Arena accommodates the Belfast Giants, one of the biggest ice hockey clubs in the UK.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Featuring Canadian, ex-NHL players, the club competes the British Elite Ice Hockey League.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Belfast was the home town of former Manchester United player George Best, the 1968 European Footballer of the Year, who died in November 2005.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] On the day he was buried in the city, 100,000 people lined the route from his home on the Cregagh Road to Roselawn cemetery.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Since his death the City Airport was named after him and a trust has been set up to fund a memorial to him in the city centre.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Other sportspeople celebrated in the city include double world snooker champion Alex "Hurricane" Higgins and world champion boxers Wayne McCullough, Rinty Monaghan and Carl Frampton.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] During the winter solstice, the shortest day of the year, local sunset is before 16:00 while sunrise is around 08:45.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] At the summer solstice in June, the sun sets after 22:00 and rises before 05:00.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] For this northern latitude, thanks to the influence of the Gulf Stream and North Atlantic Drift, Belfast has a comparatively mild climate.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] In summer the temperatures rarely range above 25 °C (77 °F) or dip in winter below −5 °C (23 °F).
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] The maritime influence, also ensures that the city gets significant precipitation.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] On 157 days in an average year, rainfall is greater than 1 mm.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] Average annual rainfall is 846 mm (33.3 in), less than areas of northern England or most of Scotland, but higher than Dublin or the south-east coast of Ireland.
[src:ram-raiding/belfast-p02] With its moderate temperatures and abundant rainfall, Belfast's climate is defined as a temperate oceanic climate (Cfb in the Köppen climate classification system), a classification it shares with most of northwest Europe.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A **black market** is a clandestine market or series of transactions that has some aspect of illegality, or is not compliant with an institutional set of rules.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] If the rule defines the set of goods and services whose production and distribution are prohibited or restricted by law, non-compliance with the rule constitutes a black-market trade since the transaction itself is illegal.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Such transactions include the illegal drug trade, prostitution (where prohibited), illegal currency transactions, and human trafficking.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Participants often conceal illegal behavior from government authorities or regulators.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Cash remains the preferred medium of exchange for illegal transactions, as it is more difficult to trace.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Common reasons for engaging in black market activity include trading contraband, avoiding taxes or regulations, or evading price controls and rationing.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Such activities are generally referred to using the definite article, e.g., "the black market in bush meat".
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The black market is distinct from the grey market, in which commodities are distributed through channels that, while legal, are unofficial, unauthorized, or unintended by the original manufacturer, and the white market, in which trade is legal and official.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The literature on the black market has not established a common terminology and has instead offered many synonyms including subterranean, hidden, grey, shadow, informal, clandestine, illegal, unobserved, unreported, unrecorded, second, parallel, and black.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] There is no single underground economy; there are many.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] These underground economies are omnipresent, existing in market oriented as well as in centrally planned nations, be they developed or developing.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Those engaged in underground activities circumvent, escape, or are excluded from the institutional system of rules, rights, regulations, and enforcement penalties that govern formal agents engaged in production and exchange.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The "illegal economy" consists of economic activities pursued in violation of legal statutes that define the scope of legitimate forms of commerce.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Illegal-economy participants produce and distribute prohibited goods and services, such as drugs, weapons, and prostitution.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The "unreported economy" circumvents or evades institutionally established fiscal rules as codified in the tax code.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A summary measure of the unreported economy is the amount of income that should be reported to the tax authority but is not so reported.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A complementary measure of the unreported economy is the "tax gap": the difference between the amount of tax revenues due to the fiscal authority and the amount of tax revenue actually collected.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In the U.S. unreported income is estimated to be $2 trillion resulting in a "tax gap" of $450–600 billion.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The "unrecorded economy" circumvents the institutional rules that define the reporting requirements of government statistical agencies.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A summary measure of the unrecorded economy is the amount of unrecorded income, namely the amount of income that should (under existing rules and conventions) be recorded in national accounting systems (e.g., National Income and Product Accounts) but is not.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Unrecorded income is a particular problem in transition countries that switched from a socialist accounting system to UN standard national accounting.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] New methods have been proposed for estimating the size of the unrecorded (non-observed) economy.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] However little consensus exists on the size of the unreported economies of transitional countries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The "informal economy" circumvents the costs of, and is excluded from the benefits and rights incorporated in, the laws and administrative rules covering property relationships, commercial licensing, labor contracts, torts, financial credit, and social security systems.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A summary measure of the informal economy is the income generated by economic agents that operate informally.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The informal sector is part of an economy that is not taxed, monitored by the government, or included in the gross national product (GNP), unlike the formal economy.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In developed countries, the informal sector is characterized by unreported employment.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] This is hidden from the state for tax, social security, or labor law purposes but is legal in other aspects.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The term *black market* can also be used in reference to a specific part of the economy in which contraband is traded.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] However, in some situations, consumers may conclude that they are better off using black market services, particularly when government regulations hinder what would otherwise be a legitimate competitive service.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] For example, in Baltimore, many consumers actively prefer illegal taxi operations, citing that they are more available, convenient, and fairly priced.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Prostitution is illegal or highly regulated in some countries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] This demonstrates the underground economy, because of consistent high demand from customers, relatively high pay, but labor-intensive and low-skilled work, which attracts a continual supply of workers.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] While prostitution exists in every country, studies show that it tends to flourish more in poorer countries, and in areas with large numbers of unattached men, such as around military bases.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] For instance, an empirical study showed that the supply of prostitutes rose abruptly in Denver and Minneapolis in 2008 when the Democratic and Republican National Conventions took place there.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Prostitutes in the black market generally operate with some degree of secrecy, sometimes negotiating prices and activities through codewords and subtle gestures.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In countries such as Germany or the Netherlands, where prostitution is legal but regulated, illegal prostitutes exist whose services are offered more cheaply without regard for the legal requirements or procedures—health checks, standards of accommodation, and so on.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In other countries, such as Nicaragua, where legal prostitution is regulated, hotels may require both parties to identify themselves, to prevent child prostitution.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Personally identifying information, financial information like credit card and bank account information, and medical data are bought and sold, mostly in darknet markets.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] People increase the value of the stolen data by aggregating it with publicly available data, and selling it again for a profit, increasing the damage that can be done to the people whose data was stolen.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] From the late 19th and early 20th centuries, many countries began to ban the possession or use of some recreational drugs, such as in the United States' war on drugs.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Many people nonetheless continue to use illegal drugs, and a black market exists to supply them.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Despite law enforcement efforts to intercept them, demand remains high, providing a large profit motive for organized criminal groups to keep drugs supplied.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The United Nations has reported that the retail market value of illegal drugs is $530 billion.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Although law enforcement agencies intercept a fraction of drug traffickers and incarcerate thousands of wholesale and retail sellers and users, the demand for such drugs and profit margins encourage new distributors to enter the market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Drug legalization activists draw parallels between the illegal drug trade and the Prohibition of alcohol in the United States in the 1920s.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The laws of many countries forbid or restrict the personal ownership of weapons.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] These restrictions can range from small knives to firearms, either altogether or by classification (e.g., caliber, handguns, automatic weapons, and explosives).
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The black market supplies the demands for weaponry that cannot be obtained legally or may only be obtained legally after obtaining permits and paying fees.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] This may be by smuggling the arms from countries where they were bought legally or stolen, or by stealing from arms manufacturers within the country itself, using insiders.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In cases where the underground economy is unable to smuggle firearms, they can also satisfy requests by gunsmithing their own firearms.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Those who may buy this way include criminals to use for illegal activities, gun collectors, and otherwise law-abiding citizens interested in protecting their dwellings, families, or businesses.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In England and Wales, certain categories of weapons used for hunting may be owned by qualified residents but must be registered with the local police force and kept within a locked cabinet.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Among those who may purchase weapons on the black market are people who are unable to pass the legal requirements for registration—convicted felons or those suffering from mental illness for example.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The illegal logging of timber, according to Interpol, is an industry worth almost as much as the drug production industry in some countries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In many developing countries, living animals are captured in the wild and sold as pets.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Wild animals are also hunted and killed for their meat, hide, and organs, the latter of which and other animal parts are sold for use in traditional medicine.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In several states in the United States, laws requiring the pasteurization of milk have created black markets in raw milk, and sometimes in raw milk cheese which is legal in a number of EU countries but banned in the U.S. if aged less than 60 days.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Rum-running, or bootlegging, is the illegal business of transporting (smuggling) alcoholic beverages where such transportation is forbidden by law.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Smuggling is usually done to circumvent taxation or prohibition laws.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The term *rum-running* is more commonly applied to smuggling over water; *bootlegging* is applied to smuggling over land.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] According to the PBS documentary *Prohibition*, the term "bootlegging" was popularized when thousands of city dwellers would sell liquor from flasks they kept in their bootleg all across major cities and rural areas.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The term "rum-running" most likely originated at the start of Prohibition in the United States (1920–1933), when ships from Bimini in the western Bahamas transported cheap Caribbean rum to Florida speakeasies.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Rum's cheapness made it a low-profit item for the rumrunners, and they moved on to smuggling Canadian whisky, French champagne, and English gin to major cities like New York City and Boston, where prices ran high.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] It was said that some ships carried $200,000 (roughly equivalent to US$4.5 million in 2022) in contraband in a single run.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The United Kingdom has some of the highest taxes on tobacco products in the world and strict limits on the amount of tobacco that can be imported duty-free from other countries, leading to widespread attempts to smuggle relatively cheap tobacco from low tax countries into the U.K.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Such smuggling efforts range from vacationers concealing relatively small quantities of tobacco in their luggage to large-scale enterprises linked to organized crime.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] British authorities have aggressively tried to detect and confiscate such illegal imports, and to prosecute those caught.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Nevertheless, it has been reported that "27% of cigarettes and 68% of roll your own tobacco is purchased on the black market".
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Smuggling one truckload of cigarettes from a low-tax U.S. state to a high-tax state can result in a profit of up to $3 million.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Because traffic crossing U.S. state borders is not usually stopped or inspected to the same extent as happens at the country's international borders, interdicting this sort of smuggling (especially without causing major disruption to interstate commerce) is difficult.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Low-tax states are generally the major tobacco producers and have come under criticism for their reluctance to increase taxes.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] North Carolina eventually agreed to raise its taxes from 5 cents to 35 cents per pack of 20 cigarettes, although this remains far below the national average.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] As of 2010, South Carolina has refused to follow suit and raise taxes from seven cents per pack (the lowest in the USA).
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] According to the World Health Organization (WHO), illegal organ trade occurs when organs are removed from the body for the purpose of commercial transactions.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Research indicates that illegal organ trade is on the rise, with a recent report by Global Financial Integrity estimating that the illegal organ trade generates profits between $600 million and $1.2 billion per year across many countries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A racket is a service that is fraudulently offered to solve a problem, such as for a problem that does not actually exist or that would not otherwise exist if the racket did not exist.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Conducting a racket is called racketeering.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The potential problem may be caused by the same party that offers to solve it, although that fact may be concealed, with the intent to engender continual patronage for the racketeer.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Racketeering is often associated with organized crime.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The term was coined by the Employers' Association of Chicago in June 1927 in a statement about the influence of organized crime in the Teamsters union.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Where taxicabs, buses, and other transportation providers are strictly regulated or monopolized by government, a black market typically flourishes to provide transportation to poorly served or overpriced communities.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In the United States, some cities restrict entry to the taxicab market with a medallion system (taxicabs must get a special license and display it on a medallion in the vehicle).
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In most such jurisdictions it is legal to sell the medallions, but the limited supply and resulting high prices of medallions have led to a market in unlicensed carpooling/illegal taxi operation.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In Baltimore, Maryland, for example, it is not uncommon for private individuals to provide illegal taxi operation services for city residents.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In places where there is rent control and subsidized affordable housing, which provide housing below the market cost, there may be a black market for housing rentals.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] For instance, in the UK there is illegal subletting of social housing homes where the tenant illegally rents out the government-subsidized home at a higher rent.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In Sweden, rental contracts with regulated rent can be bought on the black market, either from the current tenant or sometimes directly from the property owner.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Specialized black-market dealers assist the property owners with such transactions.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Items such as medicines as well as essential aircraft and automobile parts (e.g. brakes, motor parts, etc.) are counterfeited on a large scale.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Street vendors in countries where there is little enforcement of copyright law, particularly in Asia and Latin America, often sell copies of films, music CDs, and computer software such as video games, sometimes even before the official release of the title.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Copyright-holders and other proponents of copyright laws have found this phenomenon hard to stop through the courts, as the operations are distributed and widespread, traversing national borders and thus legal systems.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Since digital information can be duplicated repeatedly with no loss of quality, and passed on electronically at little to no cost, the effective underground market value of media is zero, differentiating it from nearly all other forms of underground economic activity.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The issue is compounded by widespread indifference to enforcing copyright law, both with governments and the public at large.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Additionally, not all people agree with copyright laws, on the grounds that they unfairly criminalize competition, allowing the copyright-holder to effectively monopolize related industries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Copyright-holders also may use region-coding to discriminate against selected populations pricewise and availability-wise.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Copyright infringement law goes as far as to deem illegal "mixtapes" and other such material copied to tape or disk.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Copyright holders typically attest the act of theft to be in the profits forgone to the pirates.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] However, this makes the unsubstantiated assumption that the pirates would have bought the copyrighted material if it had not been available through file sharing or other means.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Copyright holders also say that they did work creating their copyrighted material and they wish to get compensated for their work.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] No other system than copyright has been found to compensate artists and other creators for their work, and many artists do not have an alternative source of income or another job.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Many artists and film producers have accepted the role of piracy in media distribution.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Money itself may be subject to a black market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Money may be exchangeable for a differing amount of the same currency if it has been acquired illegally and needs to be laundered before the money can be used.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Counterfeit money may be sold for a lesser amount of genuine currency.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The rate of exchange between a local and foreign currency may be subject to a black market, often described as a "parallel exchange rate" or similar terms.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A government may officially set the rate of exchange of its currency with that of other, "harder" currencies.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] When it does so, the peg may overvalue the local currency relative to what its market value would be if it were a floating currency.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Those in possession of the harder currency, for example expatriate workers, may be able to use the black market to buy the local currency at better exchange rates than they can get officially.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In situations of financial instability and inflation, citizens may substitute a foreign currency for the local currency.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The U.S. dollar is viewed as a relatively stable and safe currency and is often used abroad as a second currency.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In 2012, US$340 billion, roughly 37 percent of all U.S. currency, were believed to be circulating abroad.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The most recent study of the amount of currency held overseas suggests that only 25 percent of U.S. currency was held abroad in 2014.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The widespread substitution of U.S. currency for local currency is known as *de facto dollarisation and* has been observed in transitioning countries such as Cambodia and in some Latin American countries.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Some countries, such as Ecuador, abandoned their local currency and used U.S. dollars, essentially for this reason, a process known as de jure dollarization (see also the example of the Ghanaian cedi from the 1970s and 1980s).
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] If foreign currency is difficult or illegal for local citizens to acquire, they will pay a premium to acquire it.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] U.S. currency is viewed as a relatively stable store of value and, since it does not leave a paper trail, it is also a convenient medium of exchange for both illegal transactions and for unreported income both in the U.S. and abroad.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] More recently cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin have been used as a medium of exchange in black market transactions.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Cryptocurrencies are sometimes favored over centralized currency due to their pseudonymous nature and their ability to be traded over the Internet.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] When fuel is transported across borders for resale, such taxes can often be recovered and then relevant taxes are payable in the country of sale, but there are no customs checks on borders between countries within the European Union Customs Union.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Differences in tax rates can thus lead to opportunities for arbitrage even when prices before tax are equal, in a form that is illegal as a form of tax evasion.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] For example, between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland, there has often been a black market for petrol and diesel.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The direction of smuggling can change depending on variation in the taxes and the exchange rate between the Republic's euro (and previously punt) and Northern Ireland's pound sterling; indeed sometimes diesel will be smuggled in one direction and petrol the other.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In some countries, diesel fuel for agricultural vehicles or domestic use is taxed at a much lower rate than that for other vehicles.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] This is known as dyed fuel, because a colored dye is added so it can be detected if used in other vehicles (e.g. a red dye in the UK, a green dye in Ireland).
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The saving is attractive enough to make for a black market in agricultural diesel, which was estimated in 2007 to cost the UK £350 million annually in lost tax.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In countries including India and Nepal, the price of fuel is set by the government, and it is illegal to sell the fuel at a higher price.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] During the petrol crisis in Nepal, black marketing in fuel became common, especially during mass petrol shortage.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] At times, people queued for hours or even overnight to get fuel.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Petrol pump operators were alleged to hoard the fuel and sell it to black marketeers.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Black marketing in vehicle/cooking fuel became widespread during the 2015 Nepal blockade; even after it was eased and petrol imports resumed, people were not getting the fuel as intended and resorted to the black market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In some countries including Saudi Arabia, Thailand, and India sex toys are illegal, and are sold illegally, without compliance with regulations on safety, etc.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Platforms used to sell sex toys on the black market include consumer-to-consumer online auction websites and private pages on social media websites.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] In black market venues in Cambodia, sex toys have been seized alongside aphrodisiac products.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] It has been suggested that if efforts in North America to ban realistic looking sexbots succeed, it may result in a black market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] People engaged in the black market may run their business hidden behind a front business that is not illegal.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Often certain types of illegal products are traded for each other, depending on the geographical location.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] States engaged in total war or other large-scale, extended wars often impose restrictions on the use of critical resources that are needed for the war effort, such as food, gasoline, rubber, metal, etc., typically through rationing.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A black market then develops to supply rationed goods at exorbitant prices.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The rationing and price controls enforced in many countries during World War II encouraged widespread black market activity.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] One source of black-market meat under wartime rationing was farmers declaring fewer domestic animal births to the Ministry of Food than had actually happened.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Another in Britain was supplies from the U.S., intended only for use on U.S. army bases on British land, but leaked into the local native British black market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] During the Vietnam War, American soldiers would spend Military Payment Certificates on maid service and sexual entertainment.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Also if a Vietnamese civilian wanted something that was hard to get, he would buy it at double the price from one of the soldiers, who had a monthly ration card and thus had access to the military stores.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] The transactions ran through the on-base maids to the local populace.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Although these activities were illegal, only flagrant or large-scale black marketeers were prosecuted by the military.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] A classic example of new regulation creating a black market is the prohibition of alcohol.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] When such a law disappears, so does the black market.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] Sin taxes – taxes levied on products deemed harmful such as alcohol and tobacco – may increase the black market supply.
[src:ram-raiding/black-market] One argument for legalizing marijuana is the elimination of the black market, and taxes from that economy becoming available for the government.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Permanent bollards can be used for traffic control or guarding against vehicle-ramming attacks.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They may be mounted near enough to each other that they block ordinary cars/trucks, for instance, but spaced widely enough to permit special-purpose vehicles, bicycles, and pedestrians to pass through.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards may also be used to enclose car-free zones.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards and other street furniture can also be used to control overspill parking onto sidewalks and verges.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The term is probably related to *bole*, meaning a tree trunk.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The earliest citation given by the *Oxford English Dictionary* (referring to a maritime bollard) dates from 1844, although an account describing bollards as "huge posts" in a shipyard is also known from 1817.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The earliest citation given by the *OED* referring specifically to a traffic bollard dates from 1925.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Wooden posts were used for basic traffic management from at least the second half of the 17th century.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] One early well-documented case is that of the "postes and rales in ye King's highway for ye (safety) of all foot passengers" erected in 1671 in the High Street of Old Brentford, Middlesex (part of the London–Bath road).
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Another is that of "two oak-posts" set up next to the medieval Eleanor cross at Waltham Cross, Hertfordshire, in 1721, at the expense of the Society of Antiquaries of London, "to secure Waltham Cross from injury by Carriages".
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Historically, bollards were sometimes created from old cannon, buried muzzle-downwards in the ground.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Traffic bollards are used to highlight traffic islands.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They are primarily used at intersections within the splitter islands (a raised or painted area on the approach of a roundabout used to separate entering from exiting traffic, deflect and slow entering traffic, and provide a stopping place for pedestrians crossing the road in two stages).
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Internally illuminated traffic bollards have been used throughout the United Kingdom and Ireland since the 1930s, although the term "bollard" only seems to have been in common use since the late 1940s.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] An illuminated bollard has a recessed base light unit in the foundation to illuminate the traffic bollard from all angles.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The main components are housed below the road or pedestrian surface (typically a concrete surface) so that if a vehicle strikes the traffic bollard the parts below the surface are not damaged.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] In addition, most new modern traffic bollards installed along UK roadways today are made of materials that make them completely collapsible.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] When struck by a vehicle at low or high speed, the traffic bollard shell reverts to its original position with minimal or no damage to the unit.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Reflective bollards may also be used; they need no power or maintenance, and can be built to recover to their normal position after being struck.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] A bell bollard is a style of short bollard designed to deflect vehicle tires.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The wheel mounts the lower part of the bollard and is deflected by its increasing slope.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Manually retractable bollards (lowered by a key mechanism) are found useful in some cases because they require less infrastructure.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The term "robotic bollards" has been applied to traffic barricades capable of moving themselves into position on a roadway.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They have been used in residential driveways to prevent car theft.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Flexible bollards are bollards designed to bend when struck by vehicles.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They are typically made from synthetic plastic or rubber that is stiff on its own, but pliable under the weight of a car or truck.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] When struck, flexible bollards give way to some extent, reducing damage to vehicles and surrounding surfaces, and return to their original, upright position.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Some flexible bollards do not provide physical protection from vehicles; rather they offer clear visual guidance for drivers.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Other flexible bollards have been designed to provide physical protection as well as reduced damage by incorporating strong elastic materials.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] These can be all plastic or plastic/steel hybrids but combine varying degrees of stopping power and flexibility.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Flexible bollards are usually used for traffic calming.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Israel's Transportation Research Institute found that putting bollards in the gore of highway exit ramps reduced accidents.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They are also used to separate the flow of traffic, in bicycle lanes, as well as in residential neighbourhoods to reduce vehicle speeds by restricting road widths.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards are used to protect buildings and people in public spaces from car ramming attacks and accidental collisions.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Related protections against deliberate attacks are wedge barriers and archer barriers.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The bollards are effective protection against deliberate attacks if properly deployed and maintained.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] In a serious 2025 New Orleans truck attack the attacker took advantage of bollards having been removed for repair, being temporarily replaced by portable gates and parked vehicles, which proved ineffectual.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] As collisions also cause damage to vehicles, operators, or the bollards themselves, new bollards have been developed that absorb some of the impact energy, lessening the violence of the collision.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Some are made of forgiving plastics, and others are made of steel but fitted with an elastomer to absorb the impact energy.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards are widely used to contribute to safety and security.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The American Bar Association (ABA) states that bollards are used to contribute to homeland security.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The American National Institute of Building Sciences site—the Whole Building Design Guide (WBDG)—recommends in its Design Guidance that open spaces surrounding and contiguous to buildings be included as integral parts of a security design.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] High security bollards are impact-tested in accordance with one or more of three major crash test ratings for vehicle barriers.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] These are PAS 68 (UK), IWA-14 (International) and ASTM (US).
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards have become common use for reserving parking spots from unauthorized vehicles.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Parking bollards are typically situated in the centre of a parking bay as a physical obstruction.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They then fold either manually or automatically to admit authorized users.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] These bollards are often used in smaller parking lots such as visitor parking or corporate parking lots, as an alternative to boom gates.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The National Clearinghouse for Educational Facilities (NCEF), managed by the National Institute of Building Sciences (NIBS), cited three dozen applications of bollards.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] In Geelong, Victoria, Australia, decorative bollards, sculpted and painted by Jan Mitchell, are placed around the city to enhance the landscape as a form of outdoor public sculpture.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Usually they are made of timber, minimally modified from the traditionally cylindrical, wooden, maritime bollard shape, but brightly painted to resemble human figures.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Such figures – which may be historical or contemporary, particular or generic – are sited singly or in clusters along the waterfront and in other areas where people gather.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Decorative bollards have become a well-known feature of the city of Geelong and reflect its history as a major Australian port.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] In Antwerp, Belgium, artist Eddy Gabriel transformed a bollard to look like a toadstool in 1993.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] This example was followed by other artists, turning the quayside of the river Scheldt into a street art gallery.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] In Norwich, England, a set of 21 bollards was installed in 2008 in the Lanes area north of City Hall, designed by artist Oliver Creed and commissioned by the City Council as part of a regeneration programme.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] They are coloured "madder red", in reference to the red dye extracted from the madder plant and used for dying cloth, one of the city's major industries during the 16th century; and they bear bronze finials also alluding to local history.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] 10 of these depict the madder plant, while the other 11 have unique designs, usually relevant to the specific location in which the bollard is placed, including a scene of sheep-shearing, a Green Man, a swan's head in Swan Lane, and so on.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] On the forecourt of Cambridge University Library, England, a line of 14 bronze bollards made to resemble piles of books was installed in 2009.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] This work, *Ex Libris*, was created by sculptor Harry Gray.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] The ten outer bollards are static, but the "books" making up the four central bollards can be swivelled, so that the lettering on their spines aligns to form the Latin phrase *Ex Libris* ("from/out of the books"), commonly used on bookplates.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] According to the International Fire Code (IFC-2009) and the American National Fire Protection Association Fire Code 1 (NFPA-1) all new buildings or renovated buildings must have fire access roadways to accommodate fire apparatus and crews and other first responders.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Consequently, the choice of bollard styles must conform with the NFPA's Code 1710.
[src:ram-raiding/bollard-traffic] Bollards designs must take into account the time taken to remove or collapse them to allow first responders entry to the access roadway.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] The Oxford English Dictionary notes that the earliest known usage of the compound noun *ram raid* dates from 1987.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] It first appeared in the *Evening Chronicle*, a Newcastle upon Tyne newspaper.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] The noun *ram-raider* also comes from the same newspaper, also in 1987.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] That dictionary also notes that the term *ram-raiding* was used as a noun by *PR Newswire* in 1990, while the term *ram-raid* was used as a verb by the *Independent* newspaper of London in 1991.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] The Merriam-Webster Dictionary notes that the term *ram-raiding* is a noun of British origin.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] The Collins English Dictionary notes the term can be spelt using a space, as in *ram raid*, or using a hyphen, as in *ram-raid* and indicates these terms can be used as both nouns and verbs.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] It also describes *ram-raiding* as a present participle of *ram-raid*.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] Also it notes that the plural form is *ram-raids* or *ram raids*, while derived forms of *ram-raider* or *ram raider*, *ram-raiding* or *ram raiding* also exist as nouns.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] Whichever term is used, the act involves using a vehicle to break into and gain entry into premises, or attempt to do so, usually to steal the contents.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] In most jurisdictions the act is considered a type of burglary, or robbery, as few jurisdictions have defined the act as a specific criminal offence.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] The term came into widespread use after a series of such raids in Belfast, Northern Ireland, in 1979 that was covered in news reports and in countries such as Australia and New Zealand that inspired a series of similar crimes.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] During these raids, large trucks are used to break into technology companies and steal high-value equipment for resale on the black market.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] Commercial properties in areas prone to ram-raids often erect barriers or obstructions, such as bollards, to discourage such attacks.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] Automated teller machines are also targets of ram-raiding, with criminals smashing the machines to steal cash boxes.
[src:ram-raiding/ram-raiding] Many companies have come up with solutions to ram-raiding.
